largest state the world had ever seen. Known today as the Neo-Assyrian Empire, its control

3
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:26,720
stretched throughout Mesopotamia, Syria, the Levant, and even as far north as Anatolia.

4
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:32,400
In the west, its territory ran as far as Egypt, whilst in the east its rule held sway over

5
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:40,160
Sousa and parts of the Zagros Mountains. At its peak, it was ruled by a king named Ashubanipal

6
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:46,320
who would tout his military prowess and conquests in inscriptions scattered throughout his realm.

7
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:50,760
In the centre of his palace, he built a great library that eventually grew to include some

8
00:00:50,920 --> 00:00:55,800
30,000 clay tablets and that attracted scribes from the four corners of the known world.

9
00:00:57,160 --> 00:01:02,680
In modern times, this library is often seen by scholars as Ashubanipal's crowning achievement

10
00:01:02,680 --> 00:01:07,320
and its remains provide a vivid snapshot into the world that he and his dynasty inhabited.

11
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:13,160
Yet as grand and ancient as Ashubanipal and his empire might seem to us now,

12
00:01:13,160 --> 00:01:17,640
contained amongst the tablets of his library was the story of another king who had already

13
00:01:17,720 --> 00:01:23,960
been famous throughout Mesopotamia for millennia. In the epic that bore his name, he ruled over

14
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:29,320
the great metropolis of Uruk, the son of a goddess and a mortal man possessed of strength and stature

15
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:35,240
beyond all others. His exploits took him the length and breadth of Mesopotamia and saw him

16
00:01:35,240 --> 00:01:42,120
contend with monsters, gods, and his own mortality alike. So great was his quest to thwart death

17
00:01:42,120 --> 00:01:46,360
that it even took him beyond the lands of mortal men to meet the immortal survivor

18
00:01:46,360 --> 00:01:50,920
of a worldwide flood and event that still echoes in modern religions to this day.

19
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:58,120
Since the very dawn of writing, he'd provided an ideal of kingship that surpassed all others

20
00:01:58,120 --> 00:02:04,120
and achieved a fame beyond almost any of his successors. Ashubanipal would prove no exception.

21
00:02:05,160 --> 00:02:11,000
By the end of that same century, his dynasty would be extinct, his library buried and forgotten.

22
00:02:11,240 --> 00:02:16,440
The great tablets that held this story remain sealed within its ruins for another two millennia,

23
00:02:16,440 --> 00:02:21,560
waiting patiently for the day when they would be rediscovered. From that day,

24
00:02:21,560 --> 00:02:26,440
the exploits of this legendary king would draw the attention of a worldwide audience

25
00:02:26,440 --> 00:02:30,040
and once again one of the world's oldest known stories would be told.

26
00:02:32,040 --> 00:02:34,840
The Epic of Gilgamesh

27
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:46,840
The Epic of Gilgamesh

28
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,280
Since its rediscovery at the tail end of the 19th century,

29
00:03:14,280 --> 00:03:18,920
the Epic of Gilgamesh has inspired excitement among scholars and the general public alike.

30
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:23,720
Originally unearthed amongst the ruins of the library of Ashubanipal,

31
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:28,360
the discovery of its tablets came amidst a period of newfound interest in both archaeology

32
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:34,600
and early human history. Its deciphering would inspire headlines in newspapers on both sides

33
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:38,760
of the Atlantic, with this publicity being overwhelmingly centred on the flood story

34
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:43,960
contained within one of its tablets. In succeeding decades, knowledge of the

35
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:50,120
Epic itself grew amongst the wider public. Soon it became recognised that in the exploits of

36
00:03:50,120 --> 00:03:56,120
Gilgamesh lay the blueprints of those of many later mythical figures, including those of Heracles

37
00:03:56,120 --> 00:03:59,640
and the heroes of the Homeric poems, the Odyssey and the Iliad.

38
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:05,560
Much like these later heroes, Gilgamesh's restless spirit would take into what were then

39
00:04:05,560 --> 00:04:10,760
the very edges of the known world, to the cedar forest in what is now modern Lebanon

40
00:04:10,760 --> 00:04:16,360
and Syria, throughout the land of Babylonia and south to the land of Dilman in the Persian Gulf.

41
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:22,200
Throughout these travels, he was joined by his faithful companion, Enkidu,

42
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:26,760
who he loved as he would a wife, and whose death at the hands of the eternal gods would

43
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:33,560
drive his own quest to fort death. Today these central themes of companionship, love,

44
00:04:33,640 --> 00:04:38,440
and the human struggle against mortality continue to resonate, and Gilgamesh himself

45
00:04:38,440 --> 00:04:43,720
has taken on a life outside of the Epic, often appearing as a character far removed from his

46
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:50,360
earliest roots. Even then, to many he remains inseparable from the Babylonian Epic that bears

47
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:55,320
his name, which this day holds the status of a foundational work in world literature.

48
00:04:56,280 --> 00:05:04,760
But what is perhaps less known, is that this work is far from Gilgamesh's first appearance

49
00:05:04,760 --> 00:05:11,000
in Mesopotamian myth. In fact, by the time the most famous version of his Epic was composed

50
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,360
in the late 2nd millennium BC, knowledge of his name and exploits was already more than a thousand

51
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:22,520
years old. Long before Babylon was even a city, there is evidence that Gilgamesh's name was

52
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:27,800
being sung at the courts of the later Sumerian kings, where a rich body of hymns and poems

53
00:05:27,800 --> 00:05:35,320
were composed to celebrate his feats and virtues. And before even these works were created, we know

54
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:40,760
that objects were being dedicated in Gilgamesh's honour right back to the precipice of prehistory,

55
00:05:40,760 --> 00:05:45,800
and as heroic figures performing deeds resembling his own appear in some of the earliest artwork

56
00:05:45,800 --> 00:05:53,000
of the 3rd millennium BC. And it is here in the hazy world of the earliest kings of Mesopotamia

57
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:57,480
that some scholars have even argued that a historical figure may have existed,

58
00:05:57,480 --> 00:06:02,760
whose life and deeds formed a core ideal of kingship around which the literary Epic was crafted.

59
00:06:04,200 --> 00:06:10,680
So who was Gilgamesh? How did the Epic that bears his name come to be? Was there a historical

60
00:06:10,680 --> 00:06:16,520
king of Uruk who bore his name, whose reputation later offers built upon to craft a more familiar

61
00:06:16,520 --> 00:06:23,160
Epic? And outside of Gilgamesh himself, how did the famous flood myth become part of the Epic?

62
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:29,720
In this video, we'll explore these questions by examining more than 2,000 years of history.

