Finally, we'll examine the origins of an event with which the Epic is inexorably tied,

71
00:07:16,440 --> 00:07:25,400
the Mesopotamian flood myth, the discovery of which brought the Epic to worldwide attention.

72
00:07:29,400 --> 00:07:33,160
But before we do any of this, let us begin with the story itself.

73
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:39,320
For those unfamiliar with Gilgamesh and his appearances in Mesopotamian myth,

74
00:07:39,320 --> 00:07:41,880
here's a quick summary of the Epic for which he is known.

75
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:49,480
In its story, Gilgamesh is the ruler of Uruk, the son of a mortal king named Lugar Banda,

76
00:07:49,480 --> 00:07:55,240
and of the goddess Ninsun. Possessed of superhuman size and strength, Gilgamesh

77
00:07:55,240 --> 00:08:00,440
reigns as a tyrant over the city, exhausting its men and taking its women into his bed.

78
00:08:01,640 --> 00:08:06,280
As punishment for abusing his subjects, the gods craft an opponent who is his equal,

79
00:08:06,280 --> 00:08:12,760
the wild man Enkidu. After initially residing in the steppe, where he grazes alongside wild

80
00:08:12,760 --> 00:08:17,080
animals, Enkidu is discovered by a hunter, then civilised through intercourse with the

81
00:08:17,080 --> 00:08:23,480
temple prostitute, Shamhat. After adopting human dress and manners, he travels to Uruk

82
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:28,600
in order to confront Gilgamesh, where the two wrestle in the streets until the very houses of

83
00:08:28,600 --> 00:08:35,320
the city shake. Eventually, however, the two cease their battle, and Enkidu instead becomes

84
00:08:35,320 --> 00:08:40,680
Gilgamesh's dearest friend, who he loves as he would a wife and who he frequently refers to

85
00:08:40,680 --> 00:08:47,880
as the axe by his side. After this, a restless Gilgamesh then proposes a journey to the cedar

86
00:08:47,880 --> 00:08:53,080
forest in honour of the sun god Shamash, where he intends to slay its monstrous guardian,

87
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:59,640
Humbaba. With Shamash's help, the two journey to the forest and overcome Humbaba,

88
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:06,120
then construct a raft from the cedar trees to return to Uruk. On arriving back in the city,

89
00:09:06,120 --> 00:09:11,640
Gilgamesh then draws the eye of the goddess of love, Ishtar, who rejects her offer of marriage

90
00:09:11,640 --> 00:09:18,120
due to her mistreatment of her former suitors. Angered by Gilgamesh's refusal, Ishtar then

91
00:09:18,120 --> 00:09:23,720
forces her father Anu to unleash the mighty bull of heaven, which devastates Uruk and its people.

92
00:09:25,320 --> 00:09:30,520
Together, Gilgamesh and Enkidu overcome this bull, whose horns Gilgamesh dedicates to his

93
00:09:30,520 --> 00:09:36,360
father, Lugalbanda, whilst Enkidu tears off the bull's right haunch and hurls it in Ishtar's face.

94
00:09:36,840 --> 00:09:41,880
As peace seems to have been restored to Uruk, Enkidu has a dream of a gathering of the gods,

95
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:46,680
in which the great gods Anu and Enlil decree that for the crimes of slaying both the bull

96
00:09:46,680 --> 00:09:54,440
and Humbaba, Enkidu must die. Struck down by the gods, Enkidu curses the hunter and the

97
00:09:54,440 --> 00:10:00,040
prostitute who civilised him from his deathbed, only to be rebuked by Shamash, who reminds him

98
00:10:00,760 --> 00:10:04,200
of all the good he has experienced in life because of the two.

99
00:10:05,480 --> 00:10:10,760
After Enkidu's death, so great is Gilgamesh's grief that he refuses to leave his side for

100
00:10:10,760 --> 00:10:16,360
six days and seven nights, only permitting his friend's body to be buried after a maggot dropped

101
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:22,280
from its nose. In his mourning for his lost brother, Gilgamesh tears out his hair and

102
00:10:22,280 --> 00:10:28,040
clothes himself in the skins of wild animals, then erects a grand statue in tribute to Enkidu.

103
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:34,040
Now fearful of his own death, Gilgamesh sets out to find his ancestor, Utnapishtim, and his wife,

104
00:10:34,040 --> 00:10:40,840
who we are told were granted immortality by the gods. Traveling to the Twin Peaks of Mount Mashu

105
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:46,360
at the ends of the earth, he finds a tunnel that no mortal has entered, guarded by a scorpion man

106
00:10:46,360 --> 00:10:52,440
and his wife. Ignoring the man's warnings, he proceeds through the darkness of the tunnel,

107
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:56,200
eventually emerging in a fertile land known as the Garden of the Gods.

108
00:10:58,440 --> 00:11:03,320
After killing a group of lions and dressing himself in their skins, he recounts his tale to

109
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:10,040
an alewife, who directs him to Utnapishtim's boatman, Urshibani. After Gilgamesh has first

110
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:15,000
destroyed the enigmatic stone ones that allowed Urshibani to travel across the waters of death

111
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:21,640
to Utnapishtim, the boatman instructs Gilgamesh to cut down 120 trees and to fashion them into poles.

112
00:11:23,240 --> 00:11:27,080
Crossing the waters, they arrive at a place known as the mouth of the rivers,

113
00:11:27,160 --> 00:11:33,160
where Utnapishtim and his wife live. After observing Utnapishtim and finding him much

114
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:37,800
the same as himself, Gilgamesh asks him how he came to receive immortality,

115
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:42,360
and Utnapishtim tells him of the great flood sent by the gods to drown mankind.

116
00:11:44,760 --> 00:11:49,960
As a survivor of this flood, Utnapishtim was granted immortality by the king of the gods,

117
00:11:49,960 --> 00:11:52,680
Enlil, who placed him to live at the mouth of the rivers.

118
00:11:53,240 --> 00:12:00,040
Utnapishtim then offers Gilgamesh his own chance at immortality, if only he can stay awake for

119
00:12:00,040 --> 00:12:06,440
seven days and nights. Despite his best efforts, Gilgamesh soon falls asleep,

120
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:11,720
waking to discover that seven days have passed, as shown by the bread rations that Utnapishtim's

121
00:12:11,720 --> 00:12:18,760
wife has left by his side. Despite Gilgamesh's failure, Utnapishtim gives him another test,

122
00:12:18,840 --> 00:12:24,120
sending Gilgamesh in search of a special plant from the ocean floor that will rejuvenate anyone

123
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:30,760
who consumes it. Gilgamesh succeeds in retrieving the plant, only for it to be stolen by a serpent

124
00:12:30,760 --> 00:12:37,480
whilst he bathes. Disheartened by his failure, Gilgamesh returns to Uruk, where the main body

125
00:12:37,480 --> 00:12:42,120
of the epic ends, with him marveling to a shabbani at the great city wall he has built.

126
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:47,800
Then in a final, somewhat tacked-on tablet, Gilgamesh sends an inexplicably alive Enkidu to

127
00:12:47,800 --> 00:12:53,560
retrieve a toy from the Neverworld, only for him to be captured by the dead. With the help of

128
00:12:53,560 --> 00:12:58,920
the god Shamash, Gilgamesh then raises Enkidu's shade to the land above, which then informs him

129
00:12:58,920 --> 00:13:04,360
of the grim conditions of the underworld, and of Gilgamesh's future role as the judge of the dead.

130
00:13:06,520 --> 00:13:09,880
So we now have a general idea of the epic's content.

131
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:15,240
But if we are to understand the context of the events that it depicts, along with the timeline of

132
00:13:15,240 --> 00:13:19,400
its wider development, we will also need to familiarise ourselves with its setting,

133
00:13:19,400 --> 00:13:25,880
the Mesopotamian world of the third millennium BC. For it is in this period that not only is the

134
00:13:25,880 --> 00:13:31,640
epic itself set, but that we can also be reasonably sure that any historical Gilgamesh would also

135
00:13:31,640 --> 00:13:37,560
have reigned. And in examining this world, we will gain an understanding not only of its society

136
00:13:37,800 --> 00:13:43,880
and wider geography, but we will also see the underlying motivations of its characters.

137
00:13:45,720 --> 00:13:49,960
Let us begin then. Towards the end of the previous millennium,

138
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:53,640
this region had seen the emergence of the world's first known cities throughout the

139
00:13:53,640 --> 00:14:00,280
plains of southern and central Mesopotamia. Of these by far the largest was the mega site of Uruk,

140
00:14:00,280 --> 00:14:04,760
which appears to have exerted a strong cultural influence over the other growing centres of the

141
00:14:04,840 --> 00:14:09,800
Alluvial plain, along with major economic influence throughout much of the ancient Middle East.

142
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:15,480
As with the other settlements of the region, life in Uruk revolved around the hierarchies

143
00:14:15,480 --> 00:14:20,920
of its monumental temple districts, each of which were dedicated to the cult of a major deity.

144
00:14:21,960 --> 00:14:26,280
In addition to their role in the religious life of these settlements, these districts appeared

145
00:14:26,280 --> 00:14:30,520
to have acted as distribution centres for a portion of the city's populace, with their

146
00:14:30,520 --> 00:14:37,320
dedicated work being rewarded with fixed amounts of rations. It is also in the context of this system

147
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:42,200
that the world's earliest known written script, Protokinaeiform, appears to have emerged.

148
00:14:43,400 --> 00:14:46,520
This early writing consisted of a complex system of signs,

149
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:51,240
impressed onto clay tablets with a reed stylus, that were used at Uruk and other sites throughout

150
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:57,080
the Middle East to administrate their complex temple hierarchies. By far the majority of these

151
00:14:57,080 --> 00:15:02,200
tablets were used to record the receipt of goods by the temple, such as grain, dairy products,

152
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:08,040
and textiles, along with their distribution to its attendant workforce. The remaining tablets

153
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:12,840
consist of long lists of objects, places, and animals, and there is no evidence at this early

154
00:15:12,840 --> 00:15:19,080
date for writing menus in anything other than an administrative context. This Uruk-inferenced

155
00:15:19,080 --> 00:15:25,480
trade system continued until around the years 3200-3100 BC, when it appears to have faltered.

156
00:15:25,480 --> 00:15:31,320
The exact cause of its collapse is still uncertain, although it is possible that it coincided with

157
00:15:31,320 --> 00:15:36,280
a change in the local climate that saw much of the Middle East become both drier and colder than

158
00:15:36,280 --> 00:15:42,520
in the previous millennium. Whatever its cause, the result was that Mesopotamian influence became

159
00:15:42,520 --> 00:15:49,240
restricted to the alluvial plain. In places such as Syria, the Levant, and the Iranian Poteau,

160
00:15:49,240 --> 00:15:54,280
we see the abandonment of Protokinaeiform writing and a resurgence of local pottery styles.

161
00:15:55,720 --> 00:16:00,760
Mesopotamia itself entered the period known as the Gemdet Nasser, characterised by a change from

162
00:16:00,760 --> 00:16:05,800
the manufacture of more plain styles of pottery to that of painted pottery with a distinctive purple

163
00:16:05,800 --> 00:16:11,720
colouring. Other than this pottery, however, the Gemdet Nasser appears to have gladly continued

164
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:17,880
the practices of the preceding Uruk period. Protokinaeiform writing also continued to be

165
00:16:17,880 --> 00:16:22,360
developed throughout this time, and we know from lists of city names dating to this period

166
00:16:22,360 --> 00:16:27,160
that the individual settlements of the Mesopotamian plain were already engaged in complex political

167
00:16:27,160 --> 00:16:32,360
and economic relationships with one another. A common religious system may also have been

168
00:16:32,360 --> 00:16:38,200
in place throughout the region, with its focus being the city of Uruk. This is demonstrated by

169
00:16:38,200 --> 00:16:42,920
tablets and clay ceilings that have been interpreted as offerings, presented from other settlements

170
00:16:42,920 --> 00:16:46,920
to its goddess Inanna, also known under her later name Abishtar.

171
00:16:58,360 --> 00:17:03,320
Compared to the Uruk period before it, the Gemdet Nasser appears to have been short-lived,

172
00:17:03,320 --> 00:17:06,840
to the point where there is still some debate as to whether it should be considered a separate

173
00:17:06,840 --> 00:17:13,960
archaeological period at all. By comparison, its successor, the early dynastic period,

174
00:17:13,960 --> 00:17:18,360
would last for much of the third millennium BC, and saw the rise of one of the world's most

175
00:17:18,360 --> 00:17:29,240
iconic early civilisations, the Sumerians. Throughout the early part of this period,

176
00:17:29,240 --> 00:17:33,880
we begin to see increasing growth of individual settlements into major urban centres throughout

177
00:17:33,880 --> 00:17:40,840
both southern and central Mesopotamia. While Uruk remained a key player in the politics of the region,

178
00:17:40,840 --> 00:17:46,840
it now had to compete with other prominent city-states such as Ur, Lagash, Uma and Kish,

179
00:17:46,840 --> 00:17:52,360
each of which controlled varying degrees of territory. Generally speaking, the influence

180
00:17:52,360 --> 00:17:56,200
of each of these cities was limited to its surrounding agricultural land, which would

181
00:17:56,200 --> 00:18:00,920
have stretched in a narrow band along either the river Euphrates or the Tigris for an average of

182
00:18:00,920 --> 00:18:07,560
10 to 15 kilometres in either direction. Between them lay a patchwork mosaic of alluvial deserts,

183
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:12,760
resource-rich swamps and marshland, and patches of less-inhabited steppe that were often used

184
00:18:12,760 --> 00:18:18,600
for seasonal grazing. Each city also seems to have become recognised as a dwelling place of a

185
00:18:18,600 --> 00:18:23,720
number of gods and goddesses that were joined into a more unified pantheon, and at an unclear

186
00:18:23,720 --> 00:18:28,600
point the centre of Mesopotamian religion transferred from the cult of Inanna to Uruk,

187
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:35,240
to the cult of Enlil at Nipur. Inside the cities themselves, the temple authorities that dominated

188
00:18:35,240 --> 00:18:40,200
vertical and economic life throughout the Uruk period also remained, though increasingly their

189
00:18:40,200 --> 00:18:45,560
power was counterbalanced by a new group of figures under the titles of Em, Ensi and Lugal.

190
00:18:46,840 --> 00:18:51,640
Commonly referred to as kings by modern archaeologists, how exactly these figures emerged

191
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:56,280
is still a source of contention, but it seems that from an early date, these figures combined

192
00:18:56,280 --> 00:19:00,360
military power with important political and religious roles within the city.

193
00:19:01,720 --> 00:19:06,120
Alongside the emergence of these figures, this period is also characterised by increased

194
00:19:06,120 --> 00:19:10,520
military activity between these states, as shown by the appearance of widespread city

195
00:19:10,520 --> 00:19:17,240
fortifications throughout the first half of the early dynastic period. Alongside these changes,

196
00:19:17,240 --> 00:19:22,200
many of the basic blueprints of Mesopotamian society established in the preceding Uruk period

197
00:19:22,200 --> 00:19:25,320
continued to be refined upon throughout the third millennium BC.

198
00:19:26,760 --> 00:19:31,480
Agriculture continued to depend on the careful management of water supplied by the Euphrates

199
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:35,960
and the Tigris, and crop irrigation seems to become ever more important as the climate

200
00:19:35,960 --> 00:19:42,280
in the region slowly dried out. Administration and trade was still performed using cylinder seals,

201
00:19:42,280 --> 00:19:47,800
small round objects carved with inlaid scenes that could be impressed onto wet clay as an identifier.

202
00:19:48,040 --> 00:19:52,120
Later, these objects would also take on an important role in the correspondence between

203
00:19:52,120 --> 00:19:56,760
different city-states and rulers, whose relationships grew more complex and formalised.

204
00:19:58,040 --> 00:20:02,760
Kinéaform writing also evolved to take on similar roles, slowly losing many of its

205
00:20:02,760 --> 00:20:07,000
pictographic qualities in favour of both syllabic and phonetic elements,

206
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:12,760
along with a more developed system of grammar. The result is that unlike the earlier Proto-Kinéaform

207
00:20:13,720 --> 00:20:18,600
tablets, to which we are largely unable to assign a language, this later script is clearly

208
00:20:18,600 --> 00:20:24,200
recognisable as Sumerian, a language spoken by people of Southern Mesopotamia during this period.

209
00:20:25,240 --> 00:20:29,960
And from around the middle of the early dynastic period, we also see the increasing use of royal

210
00:20:29,960 --> 00:20:34,920
inscriptions throughout the region, the names of kings being inscribed on objects such as stone

211
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:47,240
vessels, stelae and votive offerings. So now that we have some understanding of the society

212
00:20:47,240 --> 00:20:53,720
in which the epic is set, let us ask our first question. Is there any evidence for a historical

213
00:20:53,720 --> 00:20:58,360
monarch that dates from this period behind the later literary figure of Gilgamesh?

214
00:20:59,640 --> 00:21:03,960
Understandably, this question draws a mixed response from archaeologists and scholars of the

215
00:21:03,960 --> 00:21:10,040
period. To paraphrase Professor Piotr Mikhailovsky, for some the search for a historical Gilgamesh

216
00:21:10,040 --> 00:21:14,600
is a serious enterprise, whilst for others, it is equivalent to the quest to discover the

217
00:21:14,600 --> 00:21:21,080
real King Arthur, the Powered in Roland or the Abominable Snowman. A few scholars such as Max

218
00:21:21,080 --> 00:21:26,040
Malawan, Barry Powell and Stephanie Daly have been willing to entertain the idea that a monarch

219
00:21:26,040 --> 00:21:32,040
carrying this name could have reigned at Uruk somewhere between 2800 and 2600 BC,

220
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:35,880
with these arguments being based on later literary accounts and a small number of

221
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:41,640
contemporary inscriptions. On the whole, however, most archaeologists agree that there is no way

222
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:46,280
to prove the existence of such a king using the evidence that we have at our disposal,

223
00:21:46,280 --> 00:21:49,560
and that as such he is best treated as a purely mythical figure.

224
00:21:50,920 --> 00:21:55,400
And looking at the excavations that have been carried out at Uruk, it is easy to see why many

225
00:21:55,400 --> 00:22:01,240
have drawn that conclusion. In the collection of stories in which he features, Gilgamesh is

226
00:22:01,240 --> 00:22:06,440
intimately associated with the central ritual districts of Uruk, the Ayanna and the Kulab,

227
00:22:06,440 --> 00:22:12,360
both of which have been extensively excavated. If such a figure did exist, then it is in these

228
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:17,640
districts that we may expect to find some evidence for his existence, especially as a possible dating

229
00:22:17,640 --> 00:22:22,520
to around the 27th century BC, roughly overlapped with the appearance of the earliest known royal

230
00:22:22,520 --> 00:22:29,000
inscriptions in southern Mesopotamia. Unfortunately for us, however, no evidence of any writing or

231
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:34,680
inscriptions have been found at the city dating from this period. Indeed, there is also little

232
00:22:34,680 --> 00:22:40,840
evidence for monumental building at the center of Uruk during this time. The one exception to this

233
00:22:40,840 --> 00:22:45,560
can be found in the Ayanna district, where the third millennium BC is marked by the development

234
00:22:45,560 --> 00:22:49,800
of a number of enigmatic structures that culminated in its final centuries in a large

235
00:22:49,800 --> 00:22:56,280
cigarette dedicated to the goddess in Ayanna. Outside of these structures, two possible explanations

236
00:22:56,360 --> 00:23:00,840
have been proposed, the lack of evidence for monumental building here in the early dynastic

237
00:23:00,840 --> 00:23:06,840
period. The first is that extensive parts of the complex may well have been destroyed or damaged

238
00:23:06,840 --> 00:23:12,520
by a later invasion that we know took place somewhere between the 24th and the 23rd century BC.

239
00:23:13,960 --> 00:23:18,440
The second and better attested theory is that many old structures in this era could have been

240
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:23,720
destroyed during its remodeling by a later king named Ur-Namu, whose name can be found

241
00:23:23,720 --> 00:23:29,400
inscribed on the Ziggurat's bricks. Either way, what is clear is that there is no evidence of

242
00:23:29,400 --> 00:23:35,400
Gilgamesh to be found in the central districts of Uruk itself. But there is another monumental

243
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:40,600
feature at Uruk that is famously associated with Gilgamesh and whose first construction

244
00:23:40,600 --> 00:23:46,360
would be credited to him in the earliest literary texts in which he features, the Great Wall of

245
00:23:46,360 --> 00:23:52,680
Uruk. Constructed in a period when Uruk was nearing its peak size, this vast fortification

246
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:59,960
stretches for over 9 kilometers and encircles an area of over 500 hectares. Built from fired mud

247
00:23:59,960 --> 00:24:05,480
bricks, the wall itself averages 9 meters thick in most areas and its surrounding complex measures

248
00:24:05,480 --> 00:24:12,280
some 40 meters in width. Embedded inside it are a vast system of buttresses, towers and entrance

249
00:24:12,280 --> 00:24:18,920
ways, along with inlets and outlets for the city's canals. This wall is certainly impressive

250
00:24:18,920 --> 00:24:23,160
and its construction does correlate with a period when the city was known to be both large

251
00:24:23,160 --> 00:24:29,480
and powerful. But unfortunately, only limited excavations of its sections have been carried out

252
00:24:29,480 --> 00:24:34,360
and what work has been done has found no evidence at all to connect its construction to Gilgamesh.

253
00:24:35,640 --> 00:24:39,880
Whilst later kings are known to have placed votive objects inscribed with their names within the

254
00:24:39,880 --> 00:24:44,920
foundations of their major building projects, no such objects have been found beneath the excavated

255
00:24:44,920 --> 00:24:50,200
parts of Uruk's wall, leaving us unable to connect its construction to any historical figure.

256
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:56,680
The exact dating of the wall is also uncertain, though most archaeologists place its construction

257
00:24:56,680 --> 00:25:01,400
at the beginning of the early dynastic period, which may well be too early for most estimates

258
00:25:01,400 --> 00:25:08,600
of historical Gilgamesh's reign. So if there was a historical Gilgamesh, there is no evidence of

259
00:25:08,600 --> 00:25:13,640
him to be found at his namesake city, nor at any other centre throughout Mesopotamia during the

260
00:25:13,640 --> 00:25:19,640
first half of the early dynastic period. Instead, if we wish to find his earliest attestations,

261
00:25:19,640 --> 00:25:25,880
we have to skip forward by a couple of centuries. It is here, as we enter the later part of the

262
00:25:25,880 --> 00:25:31,160
early dynastic period, that Gilgamesh's name is first found under its Sumerian spelling of

263
00:25:31,160 --> 00:25:35,640
Bilgamesh, nearly a half a millennium for his first known literary appearance.

264
00:25:37,880 --> 00:25:43,160
Here he appears not as a king, but as part of a list of gods unearthed at the site of Shoropak

265
00:25:43,160 --> 00:25:49,960
that dates from roughly the 26th to the 25th century BC. Whilst he receives no special treatment on

266
00:25:49,960 --> 00:25:54,920
this list, his placing already seems to show an association with Arukh, as the entry above his

267
00:25:54,920 --> 00:26:00,680
reads Suladu Kulab, or Road Facing Kulab, referring to one of the city's central districts.

268
00:26:01,880 --> 00:26:06,360
Beyond this god's list, we also find more information regarding Gilgamesh appearing

269
00:26:06,360 --> 00:26:11,480
in a small number of inscriptions dedicated to him that date from around the 24th century BC.

270
00:26:11,720 --> 00:26:16,840
One such inscription is preserved on a ceremonial stone mace head of unknown providence that were

271
00:26:16,840 --> 00:26:22,440
frequently made as votive offerings to a particular god or goddess. To quote its text,

272
00:26:42,280 --> 00:26:49,000
From this inscription, we can conclude a few details to complement the limited information

273
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:54,840
given in the gods list. For a start, whilst we know that Gilgamesh was clearly regarded as a god

274
00:26:54,840 --> 00:26:59,720
during this period, and even the recipient of votive offerings, we also see him named here as

275
00:26:59,720 --> 00:27:04,840
a king of men, an inclusion that may reflect his dual nature and his later literary appearances.

276
00:27:06,200 --> 00:27:10,680
Secondly, we see the first mention of his divine parentage, specific with that he is the son of

277
00:27:10,760 --> 00:27:14,840
the goddess Ninsu Moon, later known under her familiar name of Ninsun.

278
00:27:16,280 --> 00:27:21,160
Finally, from his earliest attestations, we see that Gilgamesh is already being associated with

279
00:27:21,160 --> 00:27:26,520
idealized epithets of Mesopotamian kingship, with his title of the strong one being frequently

280
00:27:26,520 --> 00:27:34,200
adopted by kings in the late 3rd millennium BC. These two texts raise an interesting possibility.

281
00:27:34,840 --> 00:27:39,480
As Gilgamesh's earliest attestations in this period are as a god rather than a king,

282
00:27:39,480 --> 00:27:44,200
are we to assume that he began his existence as a deity, only later being given a historical

283
00:27:44,200 --> 00:27:50,200
background as a king of Uruk? This is certainly a possibility, but we should also note that the

284
00:27:50,200 --> 00:27:56,680
Macehead inscription does directly refer to him as a king of men. An additional factor that we can

285
00:27:56,680 --> 00:28:01,000
conclude from these early inscriptions is that whilst some of Gilgamesh's later attributes are

286
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:05,560
already present, there is little evidence of him being associated with many of the deeds we will

287
00:28:05,560 --> 00:28:11,400
see in the later epic. This is also reflected in the small group of literary texts that have

288
00:28:11,400 --> 00:28:17,320
come down to us from the early dynastic period. These texts are largely limited to those that

289
00:28:17,320 --> 00:28:22,360
have been excavated from the city of Abu Salabik in central Mesopotamia along with those found

290
00:28:22,360 --> 00:28:29,160
at both Mari and Ebla in modern Syria. The archaic and often fragmentary nature of these texts makes

291
00:28:29,160 --> 00:28:34,120
them difficult to comprehend and understanding is often reliant on the existence of a later copy

292
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:39,880
of the same text in a more readable script. Examples of this include a wisdom text,

293
00:28:39,880 --> 00:28:43,960
known as the instructions of Shuropak, later versions of which are addressed from the city's

294
00:28:43,960 --> 00:28:49,880
eponymous king, to his son, Ziosudra, along with a number of hymns and other mythological texts.

295
00:28:51,240 --> 00:28:55,480
By far the most significant of these texts for our purposes, however, is a fragment of a

296
00:28:55,480 --> 00:29:01,080
mythological tale of the love-making between the mortal hero Lugalbanda and the goddess Ninsun,

297
00:29:01,080 --> 00:29:04,600
which some scholars have attempted to relate to the birth of Gilgamesh.

298
00:29:05,880 --> 00:29:10,760
However, according to a seriologist, Andrew R. George, at no point does this name appear in the

299
00:29:10,760 --> 00:29:15,560
tale, and indeed the state of the fragment is such that even the idea of it referring to a birth

300
00:29:15,560 --> 00:29:21,240
remains unproven. As we will soon see, there are also good reasons to doubt that Lugalbanda

301
00:29:21,240 --> 00:29:27,640
was considered Gilgamesh's father at this early date. In addition to this text, two others from

302
00:29:27,640 --> 00:29:32,360
Abu Salabik have also been claimed to mention Gilgamesh himself, although the validity of

303
00:29:32,360 --> 00:29:38,600
these claims remains controversial. Moving beyond what written evidence we have available,

304
00:29:38,600 --> 00:29:43,800
it is also often noted that figures resembling both Gilgamesh and his companion Enkidu frequently

305
00:29:43,800 --> 00:29:50,360
appear in Mesopotamian artwork dating to the early dynastic period. Indeed, we frequently see heroic

306
00:29:50,360 --> 00:29:55,320
figures portrayed on cylinder seals and carvings from this period, often being depicted in forms

307
00:29:55,320 --> 00:30:01,960
of heroic nudity and wrestling with animals such as lions and bulls. This latter motif,

308
00:30:01,960 --> 00:30:06,600
known as the master of animals, is a common one throughout the region and is known to date back

309
00:30:06,600 --> 00:30:12,760
to at least the 7th millennium BC. It is certainly possible that these figures represent events from

310
00:30:12,760 --> 00:30:17,720
the later epic, particularly Gilgamesh's contention with either the bull of heaven or his later

311
00:30:17,720 --> 00:30:22,840
encounter with a group of lions whose skin he clothes himself in during his search for immortality.

312
00:30:23,160 --> 00:30:28,120
Unfortunately for us, however, we have no examples of direct inscriptions naming either Gilgamesh

313
00:30:28,120 --> 00:30:32,840
or Enkidu alongside these works, and it is entirely possible that they depict other

314
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:37,800
heroic figures from the period, or that they simply represent more generic heroic archetypes.

315
00:30:42,840 --> 00:30:47,720
So from what we've covered here, we can conclude that to the people of early dynastic Mesopotamia,

316
00:30:48,680 --> 00:30:54,600
Gilgamesh was known as a god worthy of dedications, as a king of men, and that his name was associated

317
00:30:54,600 --> 00:31:01,160
with at least one of the epithets given to later rulers. But outside of this, we have no clear

318
00:31:01,160 --> 00:31:05,800
evidence that he was ever a historical king of Uruk, or that he was a fixture in the literature of

319
00:31:05,800 --> 00:31:12,600
this time. At this point, we could easily abandon our search for a historical Gilgamesh and assign

320
00:31:12,680 --> 00:31:18,760
him purely to the realm of mythology. However, in doing so, we would be ignoring a small amount

321
00:31:18,760 --> 00:31:23,800
of indirect evidence, as a number of scholars have pointed to as at least leaving his existence

322
00:31:23,800 --> 00:31:30,840
an open question. And to observe this evidence, we must leave the world of early dynastic Sumer behind

323
00:31:30,840 --> 00:31:35,320
and examine social and political developments within central and southern Mesopotamia,

324
00:31:35,320 --> 00:31:41,480
right at the end of the third millennium BC. Unlike the largely fragmented city-states that

325
00:31:41,560 --> 00:31:46,280
characterised the region for much of the previous millennium, the centuries ahead would see periodic

326
00:31:46,280 --> 00:31:52,920
unifications of the region under a single ruler. Prior to the rise of its first lasting empire,

327
00:31:52,920 --> 00:31:57,480
there had been a number of erstwhile conquerors of Mesopotamia, but none of them appears to have

328
00:31:57,480 --> 00:32:03,240
succeeded in subduing land far beyond the south, or in passing their conquests on to a successor.

329
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:09,240
It would take until the 24th century BC before a king would establish a lasting empire,

330
00:32:09,240 --> 00:32:15,400
encompassing most of Mesopotamia. And when it happened, its founder would not be a Sumerian,

331
00:32:16,120 --> 00:32:17,080
but an Akkadian.

332
00:32:22,120 --> 00:32:27,160
The Akkadians were a group of peoples from central Mesopotamia, a region that itself came to be

333
00:32:27,160 --> 00:32:33,160
referred to as Akkad. Unlike their Sumerian neighbours, they spoke a Semitic language,

334
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:38,120
known as Akkadia, but otherwise they shared many cultural similarities and worshipped a similar

335
00:32:38,120 --> 00:32:45,240
pantheon of gods under differing names. As with the Sumerians, their exact origin point is uncertain,

336
00:32:45,240 --> 00:32:49,000
but we do know that they were present in the region from at least the beginning of the third

337
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:54,600
millennium BC, as shown by the appearance of Akkadian names in the earliest Cuneiform texts.

338
00:32:55,880 --> 00:33:01,560
And in the 24th century BC, it was a man from this region who would build what has been described

339
00:33:01,560 --> 00:33:07,880
as the world's first empire. Known as Sargon, later literary descriptions would cast him as

340
00:33:07,880 --> 00:33:12,680
a cup-bearer, the king of Kish, or even a simple labourer in the palace gardens.

341
00:33:14,120 --> 00:33:18,520
At an unknown point, he appears to have risen to power in central Mesopotamia,

342
00:33:18,520 --> 00:33:22,360
after which he invaded the south and subdued the Sumerian city-sates.

343
00:33:23,320 --> 00:33:28,680
In doing so, he deposed another aspiring conqueror, a king by the name of Lugauzergezi,

344
00:33:28,680 --> 00:33:33,560
who had recently subdued much of Sumer and led him in a neck-stock to the temple at Nipper.

345
00:33:34,120 --> 00:33:38,920
With the two regions now under his control, he established his capital at the city of Akkad,

346
00:33:38,920 --> 00:33:43,000
also known as Agade, which he either founded or greatly expanded.

347
00:33:44,360 --> 00:33:48,280
Finally, he succeeded in doing something that no previous ruler had done,

348
00:33:48,280 --> 00:33:51,400
and passed on this empire intact to his successors.

349
00:33:52,840 --> 00:33:58,280
This Akkadian empire would persist for nearly two centuries, reaching its peak in the 23rd

350
00:33:58,360 --> 00:34:03,000
century BC, under Sargon's grandson, Narum Sin.

351
00:34:04,200 --> 00:34:08,840
If we are to believe inscriptions from his long reign, then Narum Sin succeeded in expanding

352
00:34:08,840 --> 00:34:13,560
the empire to the state of Elam and the peoples of the Zagros Mountains to the east,

353
00:34:13,560 --> 00:34:16,680
and as far west as the states of the eastern Mediterranean.

354
00:34:18,040 --> 00:34:22,440
Exactly how much of this westward conquest was rooted in propaganda is uncertain,

355
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:26,760
for all we know it may simply have been a successful raiding party to the region.

356
00:34:26,760 --> 00:34:32,600
Either way, this success led Narum Sin to take on unprecedented titles,

357
00:34:32,600 --> 00:34:35,880
including King of the Four Quarters and King of the Universe.

358
00:34:36,920 --> 00:34:40,680
Eventually, he was no longer content to simply rule as a mortal,

359
00:34:40,680 --> 00:34:43,560
and in a famous victory stele dating from his reign,

360
00:34:43,560 --> 00:34:48,520
he is depicted standing above his men as a giant, crowned with the horned helmet of a god.

361
00:34:49,080 --> 00:34:58,360
Narum Sin's reign would bring the Akkadian empire to its greatest extent,

362
00:34:58,360 --> 00:35:00,680
but it also proved to be its high watermark.

363
00:35:01,800 --> 00:35:05,960
Exactly how intact the empire was towards the end of his reign is uncertain,

364
00:35:05,960 --> 00:35:10,280
but after his death, it quickly collapsed, with possible causes being the combined

365
00:35:10,280 --> 00:35:14,120
stress of a major drought known as the 4.2-kilow year event,

366
00:35:14,120 --> 00:35:18,120
and a series of invasions of a group of peoples from the Zagros Mountains to the east.

367
00:35:19,400 --> 00:35:25,080
What follows was an archaeologically obscure period that lasted for most of the 22nd century BC,

368
00:35:25,080 --> 00:35:27,960
during which these invaders, known as the Gutians,

369
00:35:27,960 --> 00:35:32,200
appeared to have exercised a loose hegemony over the other cities of the Alluvial Plain.

370
00:35:33,480 --> 00:35:36,760
Then, at the end of this period, we are told from inscriptional evidence

371
00:35:36,760 --> 00:35:41,880
that the invaders were ejected from Sumer by a confederation of cities led by Utu Hengal,

372
00:35:41,880 --> 00:35:47,320
the King of Uruk. Utu Hengal would not survive his victory for long, however,

373
00:35:47,320 --> 00:35:50,760
and in the ensuing power vacuum, it would be his relative Ur-Namu,

374
00:35:50,760 --> 00:35:56,200
the governor of Ur, who would succeed in establishing the second major unified state of Mesopotamia.

375
00:35:57,480 --> 00:36:01,240
Known as the Third Dynasty of Ur, or the Neo-Sumerian Empire,

376
00:36:01,240 --> 00:36:06,520
this state would resurrect the status of Uruk as a major centre for the worship of the Goddess in Ana,

377
00:36:06,520 --> 00:36:10,920
and embark on an ambitious cigarette building programme throughout southern Mesopotamia.

378
00:36:12,440 --> 00:36:15,320
Initially restricted to the regions of Sumer and Akkad,

379
00:36:15,320 --> 00:36:19,480
this empire would expand eastwards, beginning with the reign of Ur-Namu successor,

380
00:36:19,480 --> 00:36:24,280
Shulgi, coming to dominate the neighbouring region of Elan, and what is now southwest in Iran.

381
00:36:25,320 --> 00:36:29,080
Whilst the resulting state was less far-reaching than the Akkadian Empire,

382
00:36:29,080 --> 00:36:32,680
it appears to have been more internally centralised, consisting of a carefully

383
00:36:32,680 --> 00:36:37,080
administered core in Mesopotamia, which maintained a system of diplomatic contacts

384
00:36:37,080 --> 00:36:42,280
with the periphery beyond. Shulgi and his successors would go on to adopt the divine

385
00:36:42,280 --> 00:36:47,480
kingship of Narap Sin, with Shulgi himself demonstrating a special reverence for Gilgamesh,

386
00:36:47,480 --> 00:36:53,160
who he frequently named in his hymns. Finally, the royal court of Ur also appears to have

387
00:36:53,160 --> 00:36:57,640
established a uniform writing system within its borders, establishing and sponsoring new

388
00:36:57,640 --> 00:37:03,400
scribal schools in the process. It is in these scribal schools that we see a new period of

389
00:37:03,400 --> 00:37:08,680
creativity in Sumerian literature, along with the appearance of the first documents to shed light

390
00:37:08,680 --> 00:37:12,200
on what the peoples of southern Mesopotamia considered their history.

391
00:37:13,160 --> 00:37:17,480
And it is also through the lens of these documents that we see what some have argued

392
00:37:17,480 --> 00:37:19,640
is evidence for Gilgamesh's existence.

393
00:37:25,640 --> 00:37:30,440
By far the most famous of these documents is known to us as the Sumerian Kinglist,

394
00:37:30,440 --> 00:37:34,840
a collection of manuscripts outlining the supposed history of the kings of Sumer,

395
00:37:34,840 --> 00:37:38,280
the earliest version of which dates back to the Ur III period.

396
00:37:39,320 --> 00:37:44,760
Later versions of this document detail the descent of the divine kingship of Sumer from the heavens,

397
00:37:44,760 --> 00:37:49,160
through an unbroken line of rulers, first to the city of Eridu in the south,

398
00:37:49,160 --> 00:37:53,080
then to the city of Kish after a great flood had swept across the land.

399
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:59,960
After 23 kings had reigned in Kish, the city was defeated by Uruk and the kingship taken to the

400
00:37:59,960 --> 00:38:07,000
Iana district. In this list Gilgamesh is presented as a member of the first dynasty of Uruk,

401
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:10,120
with his name being followed by the epithet Lord of the Kulab.

402
00:38:11,160 --> 00:38:17,080
Interestingly his father is listed here not as Lugalbanda, but instead as a phantom or a demon,

403
00:38:17,080 --> 00:38:21,560
and his immediate predecessor is given as the god of shepherds and fertility to Muzed.

404
00:38:23,240 --> 00:38:28,120
For some time after its discovery many scholars considered this list to have a degree of usefulness

405
00:38:28,120 --> 00:38:32,440
as a source of information on Mesopotamian history, as least in the abstract.

406
00:38:33,720 --> 00:38:38,200
Over time however a greater awareness of its flaws has developed and it is clear that the

407
00:38:38,200 --> 00:38:43,480
kings list existed less as an accurate chronicle of Mesopotamian rulers and more as a form of

408
00:38:43,480 --> 00:38:50,120
propaganda designed to legitimize the rule of later dynasties. For a start it presents Sumer as

409
00:38:50,120 --> 00:38:55,400
having been ruled over by an unbroken line of kings, of only one city possessing the kingship

410
00:38:55,400 --> 00:39:01,320
at a time. Many of its earlier rulers are also assigned reigns of an extraordinary length.

411
00:39:02,280 --> 00:39:08,360
Gilgamesh himself is credited a reign of some 126 years and this length is dwarfed by that of the

412
00:39:08,360 --> 00:39:13,240
pre-Fudd rulers, one of whom has assigned a rule of some 36,000 years.

413
00:39:15,080 --> 00:39:19,960
Excavations at centres throughout southern Mesopotamia have also found ample evidence of kings who

414
00:39:19,960 --> 00:39:25,080
exerted a wide degree of power throughout the region, yet whose names are not included on the list.

415
00:39:25,640 --> 00:39:30,600
Finally this document also seems to have been periodically revised to take into account disputes

416
00:39:30,600 --> 00:39:36,920
between competing city-states and dynasties. For example in its earliest versions the first

417
00:39:36,920 --> 00:39:42,120
dynasty to receive the kingship is that of the city of Kish and a smaller number of dynasties

418
00:39:42,120 --> 00:39:48,120
are listed between it and Akkad. In later copies however Kish has been demoted to the second

419
00:39:48,120 --> 00:39:52,680
dynasty on the list, with the kingship originally dwelling at the site of Eridu for which there

420
00:39:53,320 --> 00:39:57,320
is no evidence of a dynasty possessing hegemony over the other cities of the region.

421
00:40:02,360 --> 00:40:07,240
Despite all these caveats there are two early rulers on this list for whom some limited

422
00:40:07,240 --> 00:40:11,800
inscriptional evidence has been found, both of whom are named in later literary texts as

423
00:40:11,800 --> 00:40:18,520
contemporaries of Gilgamesh. They consist of the final two rulers of the first dynasty of Kish

424
00:40:18,520 --> 00:40:22,360
and appear to date from a period when the city was indeed large and prosperous.

425
00:40:23,480 --> 00:40:28,120
The first is a king by the name of Mibarakisi, later known as N Mibarakisi,

426
00:40:28,120 --> 00:40:33,640
but whom a small number of inscriptions have been found. In one such inscription found on a

427
00:40:33,640 --> 00:40:39,640
fragment of an alabaster vessel of uncertain providence Mibarakisi is named as the king of Kish,

428
00:40:39,640 --> 00:40:44,600
making him the earliest known Mesopotamian king whose name is verified by contemporary evidence.

429
00:40:45,560 --> 00:40:50,120
Based on the archaic rendering of the symbol for Kish, this inscription is fought to date from

430
00:40:50,120 --> 00:40:54,760
the first half of the early dynastic period and matches well with the hypothetical date

431
00:40:54,760 --> 00:41:01,560
for a historical Gilgamesh. The second ruler on the king list associated with Gilgamesh in later

432
00:41:01,560 --> 00:41:07,880
literary accounts is the figure of Akka or Aga, son of N Mibarakisi and the final ruler of the

433
00:41:07,960 --> 00:41:15,640
first dynasty of Kish. Unlike N Mibarakisi we have no contemporary inscription naming Akka as a king

434
00:41:15,640 --> 00:41:22,360
of Kish. Instead a figure who may be Akka is attested to on a single stone stele that likely

435
00:41:22,360 --> 00:41:28,440
originated from the city of Uma in southern Mesopotamia. This stele, known as the stele of

436
00:41:28,440 --> 00:41:33,480
Ushumgao, also dates from the first part of the early dynastic period and is fought to relate to

437
00:41:33,480 --> 00:41:38,600
a land transaction between the priest Ushumgao and an unknown woman who is possibly his daughter.

438
00:41:40,040 --> 00:41:44,440
Most interestingly for our purpose this stele also features a carving of a man

439
00:41:44,440 --> 00:41:51,960
next to which is the following inscription, Akka of the Great Assembly. Whether or not this figure

440
00:41:51,960 --> 00:41:57,960
is the Akka of the king's list and later literary texts is uncertain. If so then it would indicate

441
00:41:57,960 --> 00:42:03,000
that Kish's hegemony during the first part of the early dynastic period ran at least as far south

442
00:42:03,080 --> 00:42:09,640
as Uma, which is certainly a possibility. Indeed we do have an inscribed gem of unknown provenance

443
00:42:09,640 --> 00:42:15,720
that directly names Aga as a king of Uma, although whether or not he was a king of Kish remains uncertain.

444
00:42:16,920 --> 00:42:21,880
We also know from inscriptions as a historical king who claimed to rule Kish known as Meselim

445
00:42:21,880 --> 00:42:26,920
held a degree of power in neighbouring Lagash and according to later traditions he may well have

446
00:42:26,920 --> 00:42:32,840
mediated a land dispute between it and Uma. It has also been argued by Dr. Gebhardt's

447
00:42:32,840 --> 00:42:37,480
selves that the personal name Akka was fairly rare in the early dynastic period,

448
00:42:37,480 --> 00:42:39,800
which may lessen the chance of it being a coincidence.

449
00:42:41,640 --> 00:42:47,160
In our final piece of indirect evidence Gilgamesh is also named alongside a list of later kings,

450
00:42:47,160 --> 00:42:50,520
likely dating from just after the end of the Ur Free dynasty.

451
00:42:51,800 --> 00:42:55,720
Known as the Tumal inscription this text outlines a series of rulers who are

452
00:42:55,720 --> 00:43:00,280
credited with the building and rebuilding of various temples at the holy city of Nipur.

453
00:43:01,400 --> 00:43:06,440
In this list Gilgamesh is credited with building the Dunon-Mun-Bura, a shrine that is known there

454
00:43:06,440 --> 00:43:11,720
from archaeological evidence, though these excavations found no sign of any associations with this figure.

455
00:43:13,160 --> 00:43:16,680
What is perhaps a significant however, is that in addition to the historical

456
00:43:16,680 --> 00:43:21,960
personage of Enmi Baragisi and the possibly historical Akka, Gilgamesh is mentioned alongside

457
00:43:21,960 --> 00:43:28,280
at least two other known kings of the southern city of Ur, Misani Pada and his son Meski Agnuna.

458
00:43:29,880 --> 00:43:34,520
In addition to appearing on the Sumerian king list, Misani Pada is also known as a king,

459
00:43:34,520 --> 00:43:39,320
from objects bearing his inscriptions at what may be his tomb at the royal cemetery of Ur,

460
00:43:39,320 --> 00:43:43,240
along with an inscribed bead found at the city of Mari far to the northwest.

461
00:43:44,440 --> 00:43:48,840
Whilst less well attested than his father, Meski Agnuna is known from a small number

462
00:43:48,920 --> 00:43:54,680
of bull inscriptions made in his honor by his wife, in which he is named as the Lugau or king of Ur.

463
00:43:55,880 --> 00:44:00,120
However it should also be noted that nowhere in this inscription are either of these kings named

464
00:44:00,120 --> 00:44:05,480
as contemporaries of Gilgamesh, merely that they also dedicated various temple structures in Nipur.

465
00:44:12,440 --> 00:44:15,080
So what can we conclude from these various inscriptions?

466
00:44:15,880 --> 00:44:20,520
Well it seems likely that some of the figures later associated with Gilgamesh were historical

467
00:44:20,520 --> 00:44:25,560
kings, though how much their actual deeds and lives resemble those of the later literary tales

468
00:44:25,560 --> 00:44:31,800
is impossible to say. As such some scholars have argued that their existence at least opens the

469
00:44:31,800 --> 00:44:38,680
possibility of Gilgamesh himself being a historical figure. Despite this we still have no definitive

470
00:44:38,680 --> 00:44:44,440
evidence of the existence of Gilgamesh himself, and in the absence of such evidence we must consign

471
00:44:44,440 --> 00:44:51,000
him for now to the world of myth. But as we end the hunt for a historical Gilgamesh we now begin

472
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:57,560
to see the literary figure emerge in earnest. For it is during the period of the Ur-free dynasty

473
00:44:57,560 --> 00:45:01,960
that we see the first appearance of the exploits of Gilgamesh as a figure of myth,

474
00:45:01,960 --> 00:45:06,280
along with the character that he is most commonly associated with, Enkidu.

475
00:45:07,160 --> 00:45:16,440
The Neosumerian Gilgamesh corpus exists in a largely fragmentary fashion today.

476
00:45:17,880 --> 00:45:23,240
It consists of five poems written in Sumerian, one of which has been found in two separate versions,

477
00:45:23,240 --> 00:45:28,680
along with a small number of dedicatory hymns. Whilst we can be reasonably confident from their

478
00:45:28,680 --> 00:45:33,960
language that they originated in the Ur-free period, only one has been found in fragmentary form

479
00:45:33,960 --> 00:45:39,000
dating from this time, and most of these texts exist only in copies written by scribes a few

480
00:45:39,000 --> 00:45:45,160
centuries later. Even in these later forms, two of the texts remain only partially complete.

481
00:45:46,280 --> 00:45:50,680
What we have, however, is enough to recognise episodes of the later Babylonian Epic.

482
00:45:52,520 --> 00:45:57,800
In the tale of Gilgamesh and Huwawa, we see a story higher resembling that of the Cedar Forest

483
00:45:57,800 --> 00:46:01,640
incident, though with both a different inciting reason and location.

484
00:46:03,640 --> 00:46:08,600
In this story, the eponymous king proposes an expedition to the Cedar Forests of the Zagros

485
00:46:08,600 --> 00:46:15,400
Mountains in order to achieve lasting fame for himself after his death. After amassing a company

486
00:46:15,400 --> 00:46:20,520
of young men to aid them, Gilgamesh and Enkidu cross seven-fold mountain ranges before finally

487
00:46:20,520 --> 00:46:26,840
finding a tree that matches their requirements. After cutting the tree into logs, they anger the

488
00:46:26,840 --> 00:46:31,960
forest's protector, a monstrous figure known as Huwawa, who knocks both Gilgamesh and Enkidu

489
00:46:31,960 --> 00:46:38,680
unconscious with one of his auras. Eventually, Enkidu awakens and manages to rouse Gilgamesh,

490
00:46:38,680 --> 00:46:44,920
who swears revenge on his assailant. Together, the two trick Huwawa into forming a marriage alliance

491
00:46:44,920 --> 00:46:50,040
with two of Gilgamesh's sisters, and in the process of exchanging marital gifts, they rob him of

492
00:46:50,040 --> 00:46:56,760
his auras, now conceptualised as great Cedar trees. After the Guardian has been rendered helpless,

493
00:46:57,080 --> 00:47:01,800
Gilgamesh considers letting him live, but Enkidu cuts his throat after warning the two

494
00:47:01,800 --> 00:47:08,440
would never see home again if he was allowed to live. With this done, Gilgamesh and his men

495
00:47:08,440 --> 00:47:15,160
cut his auras into logs and return home. There they offer Huwawa's head to the great god Enlil,

496
00:47:15,160 --> 00:47:20,120
who angrily berates them for their actions, before distributing his auras throughout the land.

497
00:47:20,280 --> 00:47:27,400
In the second Gilgamesh tale, we soon we see a precursor to one of Gilgamesh's other famed

498
00:47:27,400 --> 00:47:34,200
adventures, his contention with the ball of heaven. In this story, Gilgamesh is instructed by his mother

499
00:47:34,200 --> 00:47:40,120
Ninsun to carry out his duties and sit in judgement, only for him to be detained by the goddess of

500
00:47:40,120 --> 00:47:47,000
love, Inanna. Here she proposes that Gilgamesh become lord to her lady, but he rejects her

501
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:52,760
in some versions due to his mother forbidding the union. After a missing section of text,

502
00:47:52,760 --> 00:47:58,200
Inanna is found weeping by her father, the sky god Anu, who she asks to give her the celestial

503
00:47:58,200 --> 00:48:05,000
ball of heaven with which to kill Gilgamesh. Anu refuses as the ball of heaven would find no food

504
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:11,160
on earth, only for Inanna to emit an infernal scream that forces her father to give in. She

505
00:48:11,160 --> 00:48:15,960
then leads the ball down to Uruk, where it destroys the date palms and consumes the river.

506
00:48:17,800 --> 00:48:22,280
Gilgamesh is informed of the creature's arrival by his menstrual, and after quenching his first

507
00:48:22,280 --> 00:48:28,840
reveal, he vows to dismember the ball. Together he and Enkidu dispatch the ball by finding its

508
00:48:28,840 --> 00:48:35,800
weak point, after which Enkidu hurls its horn at Inanna. Finally Gilgamesh fulfills his promise

509
00:48:35,800 --> 00:48:40,440
and distributes the ball's meat amongst the poor, though he dedicates the horns to Inanna.

510
00:48:41,160 --> 00:48:47,720
In both of these poems, we see clear parallels to later episodes of the epic, though in each case

511
00:48:47,720 --> 00:48:53,640
these accounts are similar, only in their outlines. In addition to this, elements of these stories

512
00:48:53,640 --> 00:48:58,360
are also fought by some scholars to give insight into Mesopotamian society of the time.

513
00:48:59,560 --> 00:49:05,240
For example, Gilgamesh's expedition to the cedar forest is seen by Uruk scholars Margaret Van S

514
00:49:05,240 --> 00:49:09,800
and Reyn Theonif as reflecting the actual needs of monumental building projects

515
00:49:09,800 --> 00:49:15,720
conducted by Mesopotamian kings during this period, as the palm, poplar, and tamarisk wood of the

516
00:49:15,720 --> 00:49:21,960
alluvial plain is either too soft or grows too short to be of much use in monumental construction.

517
00:49:23,720 --> 00:49:28,520
By comparison, cedar wood is an ideal building material, though wood indeed had been found in

518
00:49:28,520 --> 00:49:33,800
the Sagros Mountains to the east, and we know that Mesopotamian kings from this period would go to

519
00:49:33,800 --> 00:49:39,640
great lengths to secure this precious material. In the later epic, this event would also be

520
00:49:39,640 --> 00:49:44,360
relocated westwards to what is now modern Lebanon, a change that coincides with the

521
00:49:44,360 --> 00:49:48,280
increasing importance of western states during the second millennium BC.

522
00:49:49,720 --> 00:49:54,920
Similarly, Gilgamesh's refusal of marriage to the goddess Inanna is also fought to parallel

523
00:49:54,920 --> 00:50:01,240
literary descriptions of the sacred marriage ceremony between Mesopotamian kings and the city's goddess,

524
00:50:01,320 --> 00:50:05,080
though whether these ceremonies actually occurred or not is a topic of some debate.

525
00:50:07,720 --> 00:50:12,040
When we move beyond these two works, however, what is perhaps surprising is that the remaining

526
00:50:12,040 --> 00:50:17,880
Sumerian poems contain no clear parallels at all to the later epic, and indeed one of them contains

527
00:50:17,880 --> 00:50:23,560
no mythical or supernatural elements at all. Where they do appear to have played an important

528
00:50:23,560 --> 00:50:28,920
role, however, is in informing the later themes of the Babylonian epic, particularly that of human

529
00:50:28,920 --> 00:50:36,200
mortality and Gilgamesh's struggle to escape death. In the first of these tales, known as Gilgamesh

530
00:50:36,200 --> 00:50:41,240
and the Neverworld, we see Gilgamesh's increasing association with the Mesopotamian afterlife.

531
00:50:43,480 --> 00:50:47,400
After a prologue describing how the gods divided the universe between them,

532
00:50:47,400 --> 00:50:51,000
a great storm blows down a willow tree on the banks of the Euphrates.

533
00:50:52,760 --> 00:50:55,960
Soon after, the goddess Inanna happens across the tree,

534
00:50:55,960 --> 00:51:02,200
which she takes back to Uruk and plants at the Ianna district. To her dismay, this tree then

535
00:51:02,200 --> 00:51:07,640
becomes infested by evil creatures, and after failing to gain the help of the sun god Utu,

536
00:51:07,640 --> 00:51:14,280
Inanna turns to Gilgamesh for help. Taking up his weapons, Gilgamesh rides the tree of its

537
00:51:14,280 --> 00:51:21,560
inhabitants and carves it into wood for Inanna's furniture. From what remains, he carves two toys,

538
00:51:21,560 --> 00:51:25,160
most likely a ball and a mallet, and the next day he plays with these,

539
00:51:25,160 --> 00:51:31,800
wearing out his subjects in the process. The day after, as Gilgamesh is about to resume his play,

540
00:51:31,800 --> 00:51:37,480
the women of the city complain, and somehow the toys fall into the Neverworld. Gilgamesh

541
00:51:37,480 --> 00:51:42,440
then dispatches his servant Enkidu to retrieve them, only for him to be taken captive after he

542
00:51:42,440 --> 00:51:49,000
fails to show the shades of the dead the proper respect. Horrified at what has happened, Gilgamesh

543
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:55,000
petitions the gods for help. In the end only Enki, the Sumerian god of water and mischief,

544
00:51:55,000 --> 00:51:59,960
will listen, and with the help of Utu, they raise Enkidu from the Neverworld as a shade.

545
00:52:01,240 --> 00:52:06,040
In a lengthy series of questions, Gilgamesh asks Enkidu of the condition of the dead,

546
00:52:06,040 --> 00:52:11,080
and learns how the first they suffer can be relieved by offerings of fresh water by their descendants.

547
00:52:12,920 --> 00:52:17,640
This examination of death and the afterlife continues in the second of these tales,

548
00:52:17,640 --> 00:52:24,280
known as the Death of Gilgamesh. As the poem begins, we learn that Gilgamesh has been seized

549
00:52:24,280 --> 00:52:31,320
by Namta, the emissary of death, and now lies dying. In his guise as the Lord of Creation,

550
00:52:31,320 --> 00:52:36,120
the god Enki shows Gilgamesh a vision of the gods judging his exploits in the cedar forest,

551
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:42,360
and a previously unmentioned journey to the end of the world. Here we are told he learned wisdom

552
00:52:42,360 --> 00:52:47,400
from a man named Zisudra, the only survivor of an event known as the Deluge, an exploit for which

553
00:52:47,400 --> 00:52:54,440
the gods granted him immortality. Gilgamesh is then told that immortality has not been decreed for him,

554
00:52:54,440 --> 00:52:59,080
but after his descent to the underworld he will be given a special place as the Judge of the Dead.

555
00:53:00,280 --> 00:53:05,720
As consolation for this fate, he is told he will be reunited there with Enkidu and his family,

556
00:53:05,720 --> 00:53:11,800
and that he will be revered as a deity. After awaking from this dream, Gilgamesh appears to

557
00:53:11,800 --> 00:53:16,760
seek counsel, and after a gap in the text, he is advised that he should not be sad at his fate.

558
00:53:17,960 --> 00:53:22,920
The poem then concludes with the people of Uruk building Gilgamesh's tomb at Enki's instruction.

559
00:53:24,280 --> 00:53:29,080
After diverting the river Euphrates, they build a stone tomb on the dry riverbed,

560
00:53:29,080 --> 00:53:34,760
into which Gilgamesh, his wives and his retinue are sealed. The river is then returned to its

561
00:53:34,760 --> 00:53:39,240
normal course in order to conceal the tomb, and the people of Uruk mourn their king.

562
00:53:40,520 --> 00:53:45,400
According to Andrew R. George, the poem then concludes either by praising Gilgamesh as the

563
00:53:45,400 --> 00:53:50,280
greatest of kings, or by explaining that the dead survive in the memories of the living.

564
00:53:51,960 --> 00:53:55,480
Between these four poems, we can see many of the themes that would appear

565
00:53:55,480 --> 00:54:01,080
in the more developed epic of the second millennium BC. In both Gilgamesh and Huawa,

566
00:54:01,080 --> 00:54:05,640
and Gilgamesh and the Neverworld, we see the king's fear of death, and of the great deeds

567
00:54:05,640 --> 00:54:11,240
that he undertakes in order to grant his name lasting fame. In the confrontations between

568
00:54:11,240 --> 00:54:17,160
Gilgamesh and Huawa, and later the Ball of Heaven, we see the first signs of his great physical prowess,

569
00:54:17,160 --> 00:54:22,200
whilst in Gilgamesh and the Neverworld, we see early signs of his tyranny over the people of Uruk.

570
00:54:23,480 --> 00:54:28,280
In the death of Gilgamesh, we also see his first association with the immortal survivor of the

571
00:54:28,280 --> 00:54:35,160
flood, a significant step for the development of the later epic. In Gilgamesh and the Neverworld,

572
00:54:35,160 --> 00:54:39,000
we also have an important source for the Mesopotamian concept of the Underworld.

573
00:54:39,960 --> 00:54:45,000
Here they believe the dead carried out a shadowy existence, where they either roamed naked or

574
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:50,840
clothed in birds' feathers, with only dust to sate their first. With the exception of figures

575
00:54:50,840 --> 00:54:56,360
such as Gilgamesh, who received an exalted position near enough to actual life, the only respite from

576
00:54:56,360 --> 00:55:01,160
this existence was fought to be through the offerings of libations given to the dead by the living.

577
00:55:02,360 --> 00:55:07,000
It is for this reason that people in Mesopotamia considered having many descendants to be of

578
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:12,280
the utmost importance, as those who died without descendants were consigned to the worst form of

579
00:55:12,280 --> 00:55:18,280
existence imaginable. Finally, the descriptions of Gilgamesh being buried alongside his royal

580
00:55:18,280 --> 00:55:23,720
entourage and harem has drawn comparisons to what may have been actual burial practices from the time.

581
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:29,960
The most famous example of this has been found at what has been dubbed the Royal Cemetery of Ur,

582
00:55:29,960 --> 00:55:34,040
where a mass grave known as the Great Death Pit was unearthed in the 1920s

583
00:55:34,040 --> 00:55:40,200
by a team led by British archaeologist Leonard Woolley. Inside this pit, the remains of up to

584
00:55:40,200 --> 00:55:45,640
seventy-four men and women were found, who appear to have been musicians, attendants, and bodyguards

585
00:55:45,640 --> 00:55:52,120
of the tomb's occupant. Each of these people was killed by being struck over the head with an axe,

586
00:55:52,120 --> 00:55:56,680
after which their bodies were embalmed, dressed, and laid out neatly as if in life.

