01:14:35,640 --> 01:14:40,760
Babylonian epic is written in a more simple, poetic style than the later standard epic,

780
01:14:40,760 --> 01:14:45,000
and scholars such as Andruar George have used this to argue that it could well be the work

781
01:14:45,000 --> 01:14:50,680
of a single poet of genius. In support of the latter argument, it must be said that this

782
01:14:50,760 --> 01:14:55,320
poetic style does not exclude the possibility that this version of the epic was the result of

783
01:14:55,320 --> 01:14:59,880
the cumulative work of more than one author, and that its language is merely the result of a later

784
01:14:59,880 --> 01:15:06,200
editor who formalized the text. We also know that scribes would continue to revise the text of the

785
01:15:06,200 --> 01:15:11,080
epic in the centuries ahead, and it is possible that a similar process of revision led to the

786
01:15:11,080 --> 01:15:16,520
creation of the old Babylonian version. So putting aside the question of a single

787
01:15:16,520 --> 01:15:20,200
author for the moment, what sources may have inspired its composition?

788
01:15:21,400 --> 01:15:25,480
The most obvious suggestion is that the old Babylonian epic would have been composed using

789
01:15:25,480 --> 01:15:31,000
the earlier Sumerian poems, with a combination of Akkadian translations and new material being

790
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:36,040
used to establish a unifying plot and themes, as well as to expand on events only mentioned

791
01:15:36,040 --> 01:15:41,480
briefly in its forerunners. In the process some less relevant material would naturally have been

792
01:15:41,480 --> 01:15:48,120
excised, such as the content of the poem Gilgamesh and Akkad. Support for this idea comes from the

793
01:15:48,120 --> 01:15:53,400
fact that we know the Sumerian poems were still being copied down by scribes during this period,

794
01:15:53,400 --> 01:15:57,720
and it is likely that the author or authors of the unified epic were familiar with them

795
01:15:57,720 --> 01:16:05,080
in some fashion. There are some problems with this theory however. As many Gilgamesh scholars

796
01:16:05,080 --> 01:16:10,280
have pointed out, outside of the overall plot points, the text of the epic bears only a slight

797
01:16:10,280 --> 01:16:16,040
resemblance to those of the poems of corresponding episodes, and any direct translation of Sumerian

798
01:16:16,040 --> 01:16:22,200
into Akkadian could be largely ruled out. One possible explanation for this is that the writers

799
01:16:22,200 --> 01:16:27,560
of the Akkadian epic were only loosely familiar with these earlier poems, or as Geoffrey Teague

800
01:16:27,560 --> 01:16:32,040
has suggested, that they were working from an Akkadian intermediary that only paraphrased their

801
01:16:32,040 --> 01:16:38,200
contents. Andrew R George has gone further than this, suggesting that the epic of this era may

802
01:16:38,200 --> 01:16:43,560
have been based not on the existing poems, but on Akkadian oral traditions within old Babylonian

803
01:16:43,560 --> 01:16:49,880
society. Indeed, from the hymnic refrains seen in later versions of the epic, we can surmise that

804
01:16:49,880 --> 01:16:56,760
the epic may well have been sung within Babylonian society, much as the poems before it. After all,

805
01:16:56,760 --> 01:17:01,240
if the epic were a familiar form of entertainment during this period, it would in turn make sense

806
01:17:01,240 --> 01:17:06,520
for scribes to copy it down as part of their training, or to formally transcribe a record of it.

807
01:17:07,480 --> 01:17:11,560
And whilst it is almost impossible to track oral traditions in a dead language,

808
01:17:11,560 --> 01:17:15,480
this may also explain the sheer volume of new material seen in this version.

809
01:17:16,760 --> 01:17:21,320
The best example of this is the vast expansion in Enkidu's description and backstory.

810
01:17:22,600 --> 01:17:26,360
Whilst it has been claimed that there are already some hints of a deeper friendship

811
01:17:26,360 --> 01:17:31,480
between Gilgamesh and Enkidu in the Sumerian poems, it is in the old Babylonian epic that

812
01:17:31,560 --> 01:17:36,280
we see Enkidu's role transformed. No longer a simple servant,

813
01:17:36,280 --> 01:17:41,000
he has become a wild man, crafted by the gods as Gilgamesh's physical equal.

814
01:17:42,120 --> 01:17:47,080
Describes extremely hairy, he begins his life ignorant of the ways of civilisation,

815
01:17:47,080 --> 01:17:49,640
living and grazing amongst the herd animals of the steppe.

816
01:17:50,840 --> 01:17:54,280
After being civilised through intercourse with the prostitute Shamhat,

817
01:17:54,280 --> 01:17:57,720
he travels to Uruk, where he comes into conflict with Gilgamesh.

818
01:17:58,680 --> 01:18:03,000
After wrestling with him, Enkidu instead becomes the hero's closest companion,

819
01:18:03,000 --> 01:18:06,520
and Gilgamesh frequently describes him as the axe by his side.

820
01:18:08,040 --> 01:18:12,760
Elsewhere Gilgamesh is explicitly described as loving him as he would a wife,

821
01:18:12,760 --> 01:18:16,920
and it is the loss of Enkidu that directly inspires his quest for immortality.

822
01:18:18,200 --> 01:18:21,720
The level of originality of each of these plot points differs,

823
01:18:21,720 --> 01:18:25,080
but in particular Enkidu's newfound status as a wild man,

824
01:18:25,080 --> 01:18:28,440
seems without any clear precursors in Mesopotamian literature.

825
01:18:29,720 --> 01:18:33,320
In the past, a number of scholars have argued that these newfound attributes

826
01:18:33,320 --> 01:18:37,160
are inspired by earlier Sumerian stereotypes of the Amorites,

827
01:18:37,160 --> 01:18:42,680
who they considered an uncivilised people. A commonly cited example of these stereotypes

828
01:18:42,680 --> 01:18:46,120
is found in a passage from a composition known as The Marriage of Matu,

829
01:18:46,120 --> 01:18:50,920
which dates from the 3rd millennium BC. To quote its text,

830
01:18:55,480 --> 01:19:00,120
Dwelling in the mountain, the one who digs up mushrooms at the foot of the mountain,

831
01:19:00,680 --> 01:19:04,760
who does not know how to bend the knee, who eats uncooked meat,

832
01:19:04,760 --> 01:19:09,960
who in his lifetime does not have a house, who on the day of his death will not be buried.

833
01:19:12,680 --> 01:19:17,800
Whilst these stereotypes very much reinforce the Sumerian view of the Amorites as uncivilised,

834
01:19:17,800 --> 01:19:21,640
it should be noted that they display little overlap with Enkidu's description.

835
01:19:22,520 --> 01:19:25,800
For example, the Amorites are mentioned as eating uncooked meat,

836
01:19:25,800 --> 01:19:31,080
whilst Enkidu grazes on the grass of the plains, and the Amorites do not share Enkidu's hairiness,

837
01:19:31,080 --> 01:19:36,760
nor his kinship with wild beasts. It is also clear that by the time the earliest

838
01:19:36,760 --> 01:19:40,920
version of the Epic of Gilgamesh appeared, many of the major ruling dynasties of the

839
01:19:40,920 --> 01:19:45,720
regio could trace their beginnings to Amorite ancestors, and this ancestry would no longer

840
01:19:45,720 --> 01:19:54,840
have been considered in a negative light. There is, however, another document that is

841
01:19:54,840 --> 01:19:59,160
according to Geoffrey Teague may have at least indirectly influenced the Epic's depiction

842
01:19:59,160 --> 01:20:06,280
of Enkidu. Known as a debate between sheep and grain, it also dates from the 3rd millennium BC,

843
01:20:06,280 --> 01:20:09,560
and details another version of the Sumerian creation myth.

844
01:20:10,840 --> 01:20:14,680
Whilst it is unlikely to have served as a direct textual source for Enkidu's

845
01:20:14,680 --> 01:20:18,680
wild man attributes, it does include a description of Primordial Man,

846
01:20:18,680 --> 01:20:20,760
with whom he shares some similarities.

847
01:20:23,320 --> 01:20:23,640
Quote,

848
01:20:25,160 --> 01:20:30,760
Mankind of that time knew not the eating of bread, knew not the wearing of garments.

849
01:20:30,760 --> 01:20:36,680
The people went around with skins on their bodies. They ate grass with their mouths like sheep,

850
01:20:36,680 --> 01:20:38,440
drank water from ditches.

851
01:20:38,600 --> 01:20:46,280
This text then goes on to explain the civilization of mankind by the gods, who mediate to them,

852
01:20:46,280 --> 01:20:51,800
the meds. This elusive concept is mentioned frequently throughout Sumerian literature,

853
01:20:51,800 --> 01:20:57,160
and is roughly thought to mean the norms of civilized society, including sexual intercourse,

854
01:20:57,160 --> 01:21:03,720
agriculture, crafts, priesthood, and kingship. This process shows clear parallels to the

855
01:21:03,720 --> 01:21:09,080
civilizing of Enkidu, who is first elevated from the beasts by intercourse with a human woman,

856
01:21:09,080 --> 01:21:12,200
then taught the ways of humanity by the shepherds of the steppe.

857
01:21:13,560 --> 01:21:18,440
So in the old Babylonian period, we see much formalization of the epic's content,

858
01:21:18,440 --> 01:21:23,160
and indeed its major additions from this time would remain largely the same in later versions.

859
01:21:24,520 --> 01:21:28,920
However, at this stage, much of its content is still missing, and if we wish to see the

860
01:21:28,920 --> 01:21:34,280
epic in its familiar form, we must again move forward, and examine changes in Mesopotamian

861
01:21:34,280 --> 01:21:37,400
politics around the end of the old Babylonian period.

862
01:21:42,840 --> 01:21:46,760
Whilst Hammurabi was able to pass on his unified empire to his son,

863
01:21:46,760 --> 01:21:50,120
Samsuiluna, he himself would not be so lucky.

864
01:21:52,360 --> 01:21:57,800
After an initial period of stability, Samsuiluna faced two rebellions in the south from the rulers

865
01:21:57,800 --> 01:22:03,160
of Lhasa and Uruk, along with an invasion from a new group of peoples from the Zagros mountains to

866
01:22:03,160 --> 01:22:09,560
the east. Known as the Cassites, this group of people would go on to play major roles in Mesopotamian

867
01:22:09,560 --> 01:22:14,600
politics, and are perhaps best known for their association with the use of horse-drawn chariots

868
01:22:14,600 --> 01:22:21,640
in warfare. Samsuiluna was successful in thwarting this invasion and in pacifying the south,

869
01:22:21,640 --> 01:22:26,520
claiming in one of his year names to have destroyed the wars above Uruk and Lhasa as punishment.

870
01:22:27,800 --> 01:22:33,320
But this success wouldn't last. Soon after the defeat of the Southern Rebellion,

871
01:22:33,320 --> 01:22:36,040
Babylon seemed to have largely withdrawn from the area.

872
01:22:37,640 --> 01:22:42,520
Alongside this retreat also came a shifting of the centre of Mesopotamian religious life.

873
01:22:43,800 --> 01:22:48,120
Until now, the central god of the southern and central plains had been Enlil,

874
01:22:48,120 --> 01:22:54,120
whose cult was based in the southern city of Nipur. After the Babylonian withdrawal, however,

875
01:22:54,120 --> 01:22:59,160
his cult moved northwards to Babylon itself, a move that coincided with the slow elevation

876
01:22:59,160 --> 01:23:03,080
of its local god Marduk to the head of the Babylonian Pantheon.

877
01:23:04,600 --> 01:23:08,840
And most importantly for us, this withdrawal had an unintentional side effect.

878
01:23:10,040 --> 01:23:14,600
By forcing many of the scribes of the south to leave their cities, this act unintentionally

879
01:23:14,600 --> 01:23:19,880
preserved many of the period's manuscripts within their abandoned households, including the only

880
01:23:19,880 --> 01:23:26,600
surviving copies of the Sumerian Gilgamesh poems. Exactly why this retreat occurred is uncertain,

881
01:23:26,600 --> 01:23:30,280
and it seems to have been accompanied by major movements of peoples from the south

882
01:23:30,280 --> 01:23:36,120
to cities such as Kish and Babylon. Whatever the cause, the result of this withdrawal was that

883
01:23:36,120 --> 01:23:40,520
much of the region came under the control of a shadowy group of rulers known as the First

884
01:23:40,520 --> 01:23:46,760
Sea Land dynasty, for whom we have little inscriptional evidence. To the north and the east,

885
01:23:46,760 --> 01:23:51,560
both Assyria and Elam appear to have thrown off Babylonian hegemony around this time,

886
01:23:51,560 --> 01:23:55,720
and Samsua Luna's rule became largely limited to central Mesopotamia.

887
01:23:57,160 --> 01:24:02,920
By the end of the 18th century BC, the Empire of Hammurabi was already a distant memory.

888
01:24:11,480 --> 01:24:15,400
The final century of the old Babylonian period is poorly documented.

889
01:24:16,120 --> 01:24:20,360
We know that Samsua Luna's successors remain secure in northern Babylonia,

890
01:24:20,360 --> 01:24:23,400
and indeed this region seems to have prospered during this time.

891
01:24:24,600 --> 01:24:29,400
By the reigns of its final rulers, however, it is clear that Babylon was increasingly in conflict

892
01:24:29,400 --> 01:24:35,160
with a number of tribal groupings, who a syriologist Paul Alain Bulu has associated with the Cassites.

893
01:24:36,440 --> 01:24:40,440
Despite this, when the destruction of the first dynasty of Babylon came,

894
01:24:40,440 --> 01:24:42,920
it was not at the hands of a Mesopotamian power.

895
01:24:45,640 --> 01:24:52,600
Instead, the end came in the form of an attack by the Hittite king Mesilli I,

896
01:24:52,600 --> 01:24:55,720
who sacked Babylon around the beginning of the 16th century.

897
01:24:56,920 --> 01:25:01,640
Formed in the late 18th century BC, the Hittites' heartlands lay to the northwest,

898
01:25:01,640 --> 01:25:04,360
around the city of Hattusa, in central Anatolia.

899
01:25:05,640 --> 01:25:10,440
By the time of the sack of Babylon, their control had expanded to include much of this region,

900
01:25:10,440 --> 01:25:14,120
along with parts of northern Syria previously controlled by Yamcad.

901
01:25:15,080 --> 01:25:20,520
Exactly why Mesilli chose to attack a region so far from the Hittite heartlands is unclear,

902
01:25:20,520 --> 01:25:24,840
and indeed this military venture appears to have been more of a ray to seize Plunder,

903
01:25:24,840 --> 01:25:26,760
rather than any attempt at conquest.

904
01:25:28,120 --> 01:25:32,040
Whatever the cause, according to later Babylonian and Hittite documents,

905
01:25:32,040 --> 01:25:38,200
Mesilli sacked the city around 1595 BC and carried off the cult statue of Marduk.

906
01:25:39,160 --> 01:25:44,360
In the resulting power vacuum, the city s Amorite dynasty would be replaced by a Kassite one,

907
01:25:44,360 --> 01:25:48,920
although much like their predecessors, these rulers soon took on the trappings of Mesopotamian

908
01:25:48,920 --> 01:25:50,120
culture and language.

909
01:25:51,480 --> 01:25:57,160
After this, Babylonia descended into something of a dark age, the rest of the 16th century BC,

910
01:25:57,160 --> 01:25:59,960
and sources for the early Kassite period are scarce.

911
01:26:01,000 --> 01:26:05,160
What we do know is that at some point in the early 15th century BC,

912
01:26:05,320 --> 01:26:11,800
the Kassite king Ulam Biryash succeeded in subjugating the seal and dynasty to the south,

913
01:26:11,800 --> 01:26:14,920
reuniting Babylonia into a single political unit.

914
01:26:16,120 --> 01:26:21,480
By the middle of the 14th century BC, the influence of this unified state was felt as far

915
01:26:21,480 --> 01:26:25,720
north as as Syria, and as far south as the states of the Persian Gulf,

916
01:26:25,720 --> 01:26:28,040
making it one of the great powers of its day.

917
01:26:29,320 --> 01:26:34,280
This growth in power coincided with large-scale sponsorship of public building by the Kassite

918
01:26:34,280 --> 01:26:40,040
rulers, including a vast new capital city at Durkuri-Galzoo, the central ziggurat of which

919
01:26:40,040 --> 01:26:42,760
still stands some 57 meters tall today.

920
01:26:44,040 --> 01:26:49,000
And most importantly for us, the Kassite period is marked by a new period of creativity in

921
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:53,720
Babylonian literature, along with the development of a literary dialect that would remain standard

922
01:26:53,720 --> 01:26:55,880
throughout the region for nearly a millennium.

923
01:26:56,360 --> 01:27:07,240
In the middle centuries of the Kassite period, we see some small evidence for a version of the

924
01:27:07,240 --> 01:27:13,560
epic that is still in flux. Today this version is known by scholars as the middle Babylonian

925
01:27:13,560 --> 01:27:19,480
epic of Gilgamesh, although really all we have are a scattering of fragments from Nippur and Ur in

926
01:27:19,480 --> 01:27:25,400
the south, from the western cities of Ima, Megiddo and Ugarit, and at the Hittite capital of Hattusa

927
01:27:25,400 --> 01:27:31,800
in central Anatolia. Most of these fragments date from around the 14th century BC and are so

928
01:27:31,800 --> 01:27:37,000
disparate that few comparisons can be made either between them or with the text of the old Babylonian

929
01:27:37,000 --> 01:27:42,440
version. Perhaps their most important contribution is that they include excerpts from episodes of

930
01:27:42,440 --> 01:27:48,440
the epic previously unseen in the old Babylonian version. These include the tale of Gilgamesh's

931
01:27:48,440 --> 01:27:53,400
creation and his tourney over the people of Uruk, the remaining parts of the Cedar Forest

932
01:27:53,400 --> 01:27:58,120
expedition, the defeat of the Boar of Heba, and parts of Enkidu's deathbed speech.

933
01:27:59,640 --> 01:28:03,720
We can also see that the text of the epic continued to evolve during this period,

934
01:28:03,720 --> 01:28:08,520
and that its copying out appears to remain the staple of scribal instruction throughout Babylonia.

935
01:28:09,960 --> 01:28:14,520
Finally it appears during the only ancient period in which versions of the epic appear to have been

936
01:28:14,520 --> 01:28:20,040
written in languages other than Akkadian. This includes a largely unintelligible version of the

937
01:28:20,040 --> 01:28:25,560
epic written in Hurian, the language of a group of people who ruled various states in Syria and

938
01:28:25,560 --> 01:28:32,120
northern Mesopotamia, the most notable of which was the state of Mitanni. In the west this state

939
01:28:32,120 --> 01:28:37,000
would prove a powerful foe for both the Hittites and the new Kingdom of Egypt throughout the 16th

940
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:42,360
and 15th centuries BC and would temporarily succeed in subjugating Assyria to the east

941
01:28:42,360 --> 01:28:48,840
for its power collapsed in the 14th century BC. To this we can also add a fragmentary

942
01:28:48,840 --> 01:28:53,720
paraphrase of the epic written in Hittite, the exact source of which is difficult to tell.

943
01:28:55,080 --> 01:28:59,400
Interestingly parts of the Boar of Heaven episode are included amongst these fragments,

944
01:28:59,400 --> 01:29:05,240
may indicate that such an episode was present in the Old Babylonian epic, if this version was derived

945
01:29:05,240 --> 01:29:11,480
from it. So moving on from the limited remains of the Middle Babylonian epic, it is during the

946
01:29:11,480 --> 01:29:15,960
later centuries of the Kassite period that we finally see the emergence of the Twelve Tablet

947
01:29:15,960 --> 01:29:22,840
Epic with which most people are familiar today. Known as the Standard or Late Epic is surviving

948
01:29:22,840 --> 01:29:27,000
tablets date from the first millennium BC and were originally found in the libraries of the

949
01:29:27,000 --> 01:29:33,960
neo-Asyrian kings Ashurbanipal and his grandfather Sennacherib. However according to scholars such

950
01:29:33,960 --> 01:29:38,840
as Andrew George and Mark Van Damirup, it is likely that this work was originally composed

951
01:29:38,840 --> 01:29:44,440
during the late second millennium BC, either at the end of the Kassite period or shortly thereafter.

952
01:29:44,440 --> 01:29:51,080
The giveaway for this is the highly ornate nature of its text, a style known as Standard Babylonian

953
01:29:51,080 --> 01:29:55,080
that first appeared in the Kassite period and that would remain the main literary dialect

954
01:29:55,080 --> 01:30:01,080
of the region until the extinction of Akkadian as a major language. Indeed many of the later copies

955
01:30:01,080 --> 01:30:06,280
of these texts were attributed to earlier authors by scribes in the first millennium BC,

956
01:30:06,280 --> 01:30:10,680
who themselves broadly grouped into families that claimed descent from one of these illustrious

957
01:30:10,680 --> 01:30:17,240
ancestors, many of whom bore Kassite names. The epic itself is no exception to this,

958
01:30:17,240 --> 01:30:22,920
and by the neo-Babylonian period it had become recognised as a creation of an especially illustrious

959
01:30:22,920 --> 01:30:27,640
ancestor. To quote a list of texts and authors dating from this period.

960
01:30:33,560 --> 01:30:38,280
Exactly who Sin Lake Iunini was is a contentious question amongst Gilgamesh scholars,

961
01:30:38,360 --> 01:30:44,200
such as the scarcity of information that we have on his life that any number of arguments have been

962
01:30:44,200 --> 01:30:50,680
made both for and against his existence. Even if he did exist, his exact relationship to the text

963
01:30:50,680 --> 01:30:56,920
is uncertain. As we've discussed before, serious arguments have been made that the elegant text

964
01:30:56,920 --> 01:31:02,440
of the old Babylonian epic was composed by a single author who may well have been Sin Lake Iunini.

965
01:31:03,400 --> 01:31:07,800
Alternatively if he lived in the Kassite period then he may simply have been a late editor of

966
01:31:07,800 --> 01:31:13,080
the text, who collated the 12 tablet version that remained standard from that point onwards.

967
01:31:14,200 --> 01:31:18,680
He may even have been some influential editor of a middle Babylonian version of the epic,

968
01:31:18,680 --> 01:31:22,680
that provided the blueprints for the standard epic of the late 2nd millennium BC.

969
01:31:24,120 --> 01:31:28,440
In the absence of any other evidence about his life however, there is no real way for us to

970
01:31:28,440 --> 01:31:34,040
know which, if any of these possibilities is true. About the most we can say is that by the

971
01:31:34,040 --> 01:31:39,000
first millennium BC, the Babylonians already considered him an ancestor figure of both great

972
01:31:39,000 --> 01:31:44,360
antiquity and prestige, as seen by his inclusion in a later version of the Sumerian Kingless,

973
01:31:44,360 --> 01:31:48,120
that presents him as the chief scholar during the times of Gilgamesh himself.

974
01:31:49,400 --> 01:31:54,200
In reality this listing has little bearing on fact, and is likely an attempt by these later

975
01:31:54,200 --> 01:31:59,080
authors to enhance both their own prestige and that of the text by inflating its antiquity.

976
01:31:59,560 --> 01:32:06,200
So what is there to say about the standard epic compared to its predecessors? Well besides

977
01:32:06,200 --> 01:32:10,840
its more ornate literary style, we mostly see a restructuring of existing plot points,

978
01:32:10,840 --> 01:32:16,520
rather than wholesale insertions or changes. As we have outlined throughout this video,

979
01:32:16,520 --> 01:32:21,000
the newer content found within the epic at this time also reflects ideas and events

980
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:25,960
hinted at in earlier versions of the story, as well as in the Sumerian poems that preceded it.

981
01:32:25,960 --> 01:32:32,040
For all we know, this new material may already have been part of the epic by the old Babylonian

982
01:32:32,040 --> 01:32:36,520
period, but regardless of when it was inserted, we must acknowledge that the drafting of these

983
01:32:36,520 --> 01:32:41,800
new sections would still have required a great amount of creativity and skill, as the writer

984
01:32:41,800 --> 01:32:45,480
or writers of the epic would have had to take what were only briefly defined episodes of

985
01:32:45,480 --> 01:32:50,760
Gilgamesh's life and expand them into a narrative that combined the overarching themes of the epic.

986
01:32:51,720 --> 01:32:56,680
Alongside this, however, we must acknowledge that not all parts of the epic were so successfully

987
01:32:56,680 --> 01:33:03,080
integrated. The worst offender in this regard is the final part of the epic, Tablet 12.

988
01:33:04,120 --> 01:33:09,160
Widely regarded by scholars as a late appendage to the epic, it consists of a direct Akkadian

989
01:33:09,160 --> 01:33:14,040
translation of the second part of the Sumerian poem, Gilgamesh and the Neverworld, beginning

990
01:33:14,040 --> 01:33:19,720
immediately after Gilgamesh's toys fall into the underworld. With the exception of some slight

991
01:33:19,880 --> 01:33:24,840
expansion of the text, this piece displays little to no integration with the earlier epic,

992
01:33:24,840 --> 01:33:28,280
being crudely tacked on without even a bridging sentence in between.

993
01:33:29,240 --> 01:33:33,960
The result is that at the beginning of this section, Enkidu is now miraculously alive again

994
01:33:33,960 --> 01:33:38,360
before his descent into the underworld, and its events proceed largely in a vacuum,

995
01:33:38,360 --> 01:33:44,440
disconnected from the previous epic. Exactly when or why this tablet was added into the narrative

996
01:33:44,440 --> 01:33:49,960
is uncertain. One theory, voiced by Geoffrey Teague, is that this section was included in

997
01:33:49,960 --> 01:33:54,760
order to instruct Gilgamesh on the conditions of the underworld, as he might better understand

998
01:33:54,760 --> 01:33:58,120
the role that he would play after his demise as Judge of the Dead.

999
01:34:03,000 --> 01:34:07,640
Back to the main text of the epic, what is also interesting is how the Mesopotamian society it

1000
01:34:07,640 --> 01:34:13,080
depicts remains closer to that of the 3rd and the early 2nd millennium BC than that of the

1001
01:34:13,080 --> 01:34:19,160
Kassite period. For example, in the standard epic, Enlil remains king of the gods, despite him

1002
01:34:19,160 --> 01:34:25,160
having long been supplanted as the head of the Babylonian pantheon by Marduk. Indeed, by the

1003
01:34:25,160 --> 01:34:30,920
Kassite period, Enlil had been so demoted that he barely appears in the late Babylonian creation myth,

1004
01:34:30,920 --> 01:34:35,800
the Anuma Elish, in which Marduk takes on the central role as the lord of creation.

1005
01:34:37,080 --> 01:34:41,880
As a result, it seems clear that by this point, the larger elements of the epic have become fixed

1006
01:34:41,880 --> 01:34:47,160
within Babylonian scribal traditions, with the plot points of its ancient storyline being respected

1007
01:34:47,160 --> 01:34:50,040
rather than being altered to reflect more contemporary developments.

1008
01:34:52,440 --> 01:34:56,920
Putting all these comparatively minor points aside, the standard epic stands out from its

1009
01:34:56,920 --> 01:35:02,440
prior versions by its inclusion for the first time of what has become the epic's most famous element.

1010
01:35:03,640 --> 01:35:07,880
We have seen hints of its existence earlier when discussing the Sumerian poem,

1011
01:35:07,880 --> 01:35:13,560
The Death of Gilgamesh, and the opening of the Sumerian King List. Indeed, it was the inclusion

1012
01:35:13,560 --> 01:35:18,200
of this element that led to renewed interest in the epic following its initial rediscovery,

1013
01:35:18,200 --> 01:35:21,560
and that would soon raise its profile to worldwide attention.

1014
01:35:22,840 --> 01:35:26,920
It is this event that would influence works far beyond its original epic,

1015
01:35:26,920 --> 01:35:32,040
and shape the canon of both other mythologies and of religion still practiced throughout the world today.

1016
01:35:38,520 --> 01:35:40,040
The Flood

1017
01:35:40,040 --> 01:36:09,000
In 1872, a momentous discovery was made by a 32-year-old man in the employee of the British Museum.

1018
01:36:10,280 --> 01:36:14,280
He held no formal degree, no great scholarship or position,

1019
01:36:14,280 --> 01:36:18,520
being a mere assistant to the more renowned Assyriologist, Sir Henry Rawinson.

1020
01:36:20,200 --> 01:36:24,840
His name was George Smith. He came from a humble background,

1021
01:36:24,840 --> 01:36:28,200
