1082
01:41:38,760 --> 01:41:43,400
and an account of it which has been given by Mr George Smith of the British Museum

1083
01:41:43,400 --> 01:41:48,440
has caused a good deal of excitement, especially one passage in which the gods of the period are

1084
01:41:48,440 --> 01:41:53,480
described as feeling very bad and sitting like dogs with their tails between their legs.

1085
01:41:54,440 --> 01:41:59,000
This irreverent remark occurs in a narrative of the deluge, which purports to have been given

1086
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:04,120
by one of the survivors to a Chaldean monarch named Isdoubar. The original composition of

1087
01:42:04,120 --> 01:42:08,840
the narrative is placed at the latest in the 17th century before the Christian era,

1088
01:42:08,840 --> 01:42:15,080
and it might be much earlier. At the same time, however, the paper sounded a cautionary note.

1089
01:42:16,280 --> 01:42:20,360
For the present, the Orthodox people are in great delight and are very much

1090
01:42:20,360 --> 01:42:25,560
pre-possessed by the corroboration which Cicit affords to Biblical history. It is possible,

1091
01:42:25,560 --> 01:42:29,960
however, as has been pointed out, that the Chaldean inscription, if genuine,

1092
01:42:29,960 --> 01:42:33,960
may be regarded as a confirmation of the statement that there are various traditions

1093
01:42:33,960 --> 01:42:38,760
of the deluge apart from the Biblical one, which are perhaps legendary like the rest.

1094
01:42:40,920 --> 01:42:45,160
The discovery of the flood portion of the Gilgamesh epic launched Smith to immediate

1095
01:42:45,160 --> 01:42:50,520
preeminence as an Assyriologist, and gave him the opportunity to realise his dream of excavating in

1096
01:42:50,520 --> 01:42:56,200
the field. Over the next four years, Smith would conduct free expeditions to Minerv,

1097
01:42:56,200 --> 01:43:00,520
publishing his findings in volumes that were as much travel logs as they were reports.

1098
01:43:01,880 --> 01:43:06,360
In 1876, he published his translation of the Gilgamesh epic under the title

1099
01:43:06,360 --> 01:43:10,520
The Chaldean Account of Genesis, placing its flood myth full on centre.

1100
01:43:11,720 --> 01:43:15,960
By the time of his unexpected death, he had eclipsed his contemporaries in fame,

1101
01:43:15,960 --> 01:43:19,320
and appeared to be on the precipice of a long and distinguished career.

1102
01:43:20,520 --> 01:43:24,600
Unfortunately for him, his young family, and the field of Assyriology,

1103
01:43:24,600 --> 01:43:27,240
his third expedition to Minerv would be his last.

1104
01:43:28,520 --> 01:43:32,440
On the return journey, he stopped in a small village outside of Aleppo,

1105
01:43:32,440 --> 01:43:38,040
where he came down with dysentery. His companions managed to rush him to the city in search of

1106
01:43:38,040 --> 01:43:44,040
medical aid, but nothing could be done, and he died there on August 19th, 1876.

1107
01:43:45,240 --> 01:43:47,160
He was just 36 years old.

1108
01:43:51,480 --> 01:43:58,760
The flood myth contained in the Gilgamesh epic received worldwide attention from the moment of

1109
01:43:58,760 --> 01:44:03,320
its discovery, and remains one of the primary sources of interest in the story to this day.

1110
01:44:04,840 --> 01:44:09,320
Whilst much of the focus placed upon it is due to its connections with the later biblical flood

1111
01:44:09,320 --> 01:44:14,120
story, it should be emphasised that to the Mesopotamians themselves, the flood was a seminal

1112
01:44:14,120 --> 01:44:20,360
event in history. Before it came an age when gods and primordial forces stalked the land.

1113
01:44:20,680 --> 01:44:25,720
When humanity, animals, and the first cities were created, and when the kingship itself

1114
01:44:25,720 --> 01:44:31,480
first descended from the heavens. In these anti-Diluvian times, they believed that kings

1115
01:44:31,480 --> 01:44:37,160
reigned for thousands of years, and the population of the world far outweighed that of later Mesopotamian

1116
01:44:37,160 --> 01:44:44,040
society. In Tablet 11 of the epic of Gilgamesh, we have only a paraphrase of the flood's events,

1117
01:44:44,040 --> 01:44:46,760
but even this lays bare the scale of its destruction.

1118
01:44:47,720 --> 01:44:52,600
In this Tablet, the survivor of the flood, Utsnapishtim, relates the story of its events

1119
01:44:52,600 --> 01:44:58,840
to Gilgamesh in order to explain his immortality. We learn that in a previous age, the city of

1120
01:44:58,840 --> 01:45:04,680
Shoropak, located on the Euphrates to the south of Nippur, was home to the gods Anu, Enlil,

1121
01:45:04,680 --> 01:45:09,880
Ninurta, Enugge, and Ea, the Babylonian name for the Sumerian god Enki.

1122
01:45:11,000 --> 01:45:16,040
So great had mankind multiplied in those days, that it was said the whole world bellowed like

1123
01:45:16,040 --> 01:45:22,680
a ball, and this noise roused the anger of the king of the gods, Enlil. He decreed that humanity

1124
01:45:22,680 --> 01:45:27,720
should be exterminated, and that all life should perish beneath the waters of a giant flood.

1125
01:45:28,680 --> 01:45:34,360
In doing so, he also made the other gods swear an oath of secrecy, but after the decision was made,

1126
01:45:34,360 --> 01:45:40,920
Ea crept out of the council. By pretending to speak to the wall of a reed hut, he warned the mortal

1127
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:48,040
man Utnapishtim of the coming flood. Following Ea's advice, Utnapishtim tore down his house

1128
01:45:48,040 --> 01:45:52,840
and built a boat with seven decks that measured 120 cubits on all sides.

1129
01:45:54,040 --> 01:45:59,160
After seven days labour, the boat was complete, and Utnapishtim loaded onto it all of his gold

1130
01:45:59,160 --> 01:46:05,800
and family, along with his craftsmen, and beasts both wild and tame. That evening as predicted,

1131
01:46:05,800 --> 01:46:11,160
the storm god Adad flooded the land with a torrential downpour, lasting for six days and nights.

1132
01:46:12,360 --> 01:46:16,920
Terrified by the storm that they have unleashed, the gods cowered like dogs,

1133
01:46:16,920 --> 01:46:22,840
whilst Ishtar bemoans the drowning of mankind. Utnapishtim's boat survives, however,

1134
01:46:22,840 --> 01:46:27,480
and on the seventh day of the flood, he throws open a portal only to reveal water stretching

1135
01:46:27,480 --> 01:46:33,640
as far as the eye can see. Finally, land appears in the form of the peak of Mount Nisir,

1136
01:46:33,640 --> 01:46:40,040
on which Utnapishtim's boat runs aground. After seven more days, he sends out first a dove

1137
01:46:40,040 --> 01:46:46,920
and a swallow, both of whom return after finding no place to land. Finally, he sends out a raven,

1138
01:46:46,920 --> 01:46:49,880
who finds that the waters have receded and does not return.

1139
01:46:52,600 --> 01:46:57,960
Utnapishtim then performs a great sacrifice on the mountain, the fragrance of which draws the gods

1140
01:46:57,960 --> 01:47:05,080
one by one. Ishtar soon arrives and she bemoans Enlil's folly in calling for humanity's destruction.

1141
01:47:06,440 --> 01:47:11,320
Eventually, Enlil himself arrives, angry at humanity's survival, only to be shamed by

1142
01:47:11,320 --> 01:47:18,760
both Ishtar and Enki. Finally, Enlil then blesses both Utnapishtim and his wife with immortality

1143
01:47:18,760 --> 01:47:21,880
and sets them at the mouth of the rivers to dwell for all time.

1144
01:47:22,840 --> 01:47:29,800
Since its initial discovery, comparisons have rightly been drawn between this story and the

1145
01:47:29,800 --> 01:47:34,520
account of the flood given in the Book of Genesis, where the role of Utnapishtim is taken by the

1146
01:47:34,520 --> 01:47:41,720
patriarch Noah and his family. Indeed, when placed side by side, the two stories are almost

1147
01:47:41,720 --> 01:47:47,000
identical, with only minor changes being inserted into the Genesis narrative to fit with the wider

1148
01:47:47,000 --> 01:47:54,360
biblical canon. For example, in the Genesis flood story, the many gods of the Mesopotamian Pantheon

1149
01:47:54,360 --> 01:47:59,080
are replaced by the single god of the Bible, who now has to perform both the role of summoning the

1150
01:47:59,080 --> 01:48:04,440
flood to destroy humanity and of warning the last righteous man and his family to build the ark.

1151
01:48:05,640 --> 01:48:10,600
Conversely, the Genesis story retains even small details of the Gilgamesh flood myth,

1152
01:48:10,600 --> 01:48:14,280
down to the god of the Bible being pleased by the scent of Noah's sacrifice,

1153
01:48:14,280 --> 01:48:20,360
much as were his Mesopotamian predecessors. As such, it is now widely agreed by scholars

1154
01:48:20,360 --> 01:48:25,080
that the events of the Genesis flood narrative are taken almost wholesale from Gilgamesh,

1155
01:48:25,080 --> 01:48:29,560
and that other Mesopotamian myths such as the Anuma Elish also appear to have influenced

1156
01:48:29,560 --> 01:48:35,240
the wider biblical account of creation. And going beyond the biblical account,

1157
01:48:35,240 --> 01:48:39,480
other mythologies also show flood stories with clear influences from Gilgamesh.

1158
01:48:39,480 --> 01:48:45,080
In Greek mythology, a similar flood myth concerns the adventures of the Greek hero

1159
01:48:45,080 --> 01:48:51,720
Dukallion. In this account, Zeus has grown angry at the actions of the bronze race of men,

1160
01:48:51,720 --> 01:48:55,960
and decides to eliminate them by flooding most of Greece with an abundance of rain.

1161
01:48:57,080 --> 01:49:03,160
On the advice of his father, Prometheus, Dukallion survives this downpour by building a great chest,

1162
01:49:03,160 --> 01:49:08,520
into which he places himself and his wife, Pyrrha, along with enough provisions to last out the flood.

1163
01:49:09,640 --> 01:49:14,440
After nine days and nights, Dukallion comes to rest on the shores of Mount Parnassus,

1164
01:49:14,440 --> 01:49:21,080
where Zeus rewards him with whatever his heart desires. Dukallion then uses this wish to repopulate

1165
01:49:21,080 --> 01:49:25,080
Greece, turning the stones he and his wife through into men and women.

1166
01:49:27,080 --> 01:49:31,080
So the Gilgamesh flood myth was clearly a major influence on the later mythologies

1167
01:49:31,080 --> 01:49:35,080
of the Eastern Mediterranean. But where exactly did it originate?

1168
01:49:36,040 --> 01:49:39,640
Going only by the material we have discussed so far in this video,

1169
01:49:39,640 --> 01:49:43,560
it may seem like this story is an entirely new addition to the standard epic.

1170
01:49:44,680 --> 01:49:48,680
Whilst we know that the survivor of the flood was associated in some way with Gilgamesh,

1171
01:49:48,680 --> 01:49:53,400
as far back as one of the Sumerian poems, we have no evidence at all of the flood story

1172
01:49:53,400 --> 01:49:59,720
in any earlier version of the epic. In itself, this may simply be an accident of survival,

1173
01:49:59,720 --> 01:50:03,000
as only portions of the old and middle Babylonian epic remain.

1174
01:50:04,200 --> 01:50:07,640
But if we instead look to the wider literature of Mesopotamia,

